{"title_page": "Josephine MacLeod", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Josephine MacLeod\n| image = Olea Bull, Betty Laggett and Josephine MacLeod July 1906.png\n| caption = Olea Bull, Betty Leggett and Josephine MacLeod at the Holdts Hotel, Bergon, Norway after dinner with King Haarkon and Queen Maud on July 23, 1906\n| birth_name = Josephine MacLeod\n| birth_date = 1858\n| birth_place =  United States\n| residence =[[New York City]]\n| death_date = 1949\n| death_place = [[Hollywood, California]] \n| occupation =  Religious activist\n| nationality = American\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| yearsactive= 1895\u20131949\n| othername = Joe<br> Jo-Jo<br> Yum<br> Tantine\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Josephine MacLeod''' (1858\u20131949) was an American friend and devotee of [[Swami Vivekananda]].<ref name=\"Studies2001\">{{cite book|author=Punjabi University. Dept. of Religious Studies|title=Journal of Religious Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P-snAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=11 October 2012|year=2001|publisher=Dept. of Religious Studies, Punjabi University.}}</ref>{{sfn|Sil|1997|p=187}} She had a strong attachment to India and was an active participant in the Ramakrishna Vivekananda movement.<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vivekananda.net/pplheknew/svdisciples/JosephineMcCleod.html |title=Josephine MacLeod \u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda |accessdate=11 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918021529/http://www.vivekananda.net/pplheknew/SVDisciples/JosephineMcCleod.html |archivedate=18 September 2012 }}</ref>\nShe was given the nicknames \"Tantine\" and \"Jo Jo\" by Vivekananda. She considered Swami Vivekananda to be her friend and helped him with his finances. She and [[Sister Nivedita]] exchanged letters discussing their positive impressions of Swami Vivekananda and they competed with each other for his attention.{{sfn|Sil|1997|p=187}}{{better source needed|date=August 2018}}\nJosephine was not a [[sanyasin]], unlike many others such as [[Sister Nivedita]] or [[Sister Christine]].<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\"/> She was instrumental in spreading Vivekananda's message on Vedanta in the West.{{sfn|Vivekananda|2000|p=110}}\nShe had many contributions to the initial and the later phases of the development of the order of [[Ramakrishna]] and [[Vivekananda]]. She was a contributor to many causes espoused by [[Sister Nivedita]], the most famous disciple of Vivekananda, including that of contributing financially towards the development of [[Indian National Movement]] esp. in Bengal and elsewhere in India.<ref>''Nivedita Lokmata'', By Sankari Prasad Basu, Publisher Ananda Publishers Pvt. Limited, 1968, {{ISBN|9788170669722}}</ref>\n[[File:Josephinemcleod.jpg|thumb|Josephine Macleod in 1939]]\n\n== Life ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nJosephine was born in 1858 to John David MacLeod and Mary Ann Lennon. Josephine's father was an American of Scottish descent. Her native place was Chicago. The couple had three sons and three daughters. Two of their daughters, Besse or Betty (1852\u20141931) and Josephine (1858\u20141949), became disciples of Swami Vivekananda.<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\" />  Betty married Mr. William Sturges of Chicago in the year 1876, and had a son named Hollister and a daughter named Alberta, who were also intimately connected with the [[Vedanta]] Societies and [[Ramakrishna]] order. Being unmarried herself, Josephine stayed with Betty and her family. After the death of William Sturges in 1894, Betty married Mr. Francis Legett, a businessman of New York, in 1895. [[Swami Vivekananda]] attended this marriage in Paris. [[Ridgely Manor]], which later became famous as one of the places to accommodate [[Swami Vivekananda]] during his travel to Americas and Europe in 1899, belonged to the Legett family.<ref>[http://ridgely.org/?p=276] Ridgely Manor Website</ref>\nJosephine was known by several other nicknames, including Joe, Jo-Jo, Yum and Tantine (meaning \"Aunty\"<ref name=Tantine/>).{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}}\n\n=== Relationship to Swami Vivekananda ===\nJosephine and her sister Betty first heard Swami Vivekananda's lecture on Vedanta philosophy in [[New York City]] on 29 January 1895. Their friend R. Dora Roetheslesberger had told them about Vivekananda. They had assembled in the sitting room of Vivekananda's apartment along with many other women and a few men. His lecture impressed her and she observed at the end of the lecture that the way he presented truth was something unique.<!-- suggest direct quote here --> She heard his lectures several times over the next seven years<!--  and she was always impacted by the way he presented the truth -->.{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}} \nThe meeting with Swami Vivekananda and her association with him for the remaining periods of his life in America and India was the most important event in her life according to her.<ref name=\"Vivekananda Enthralling\">Vivekananda\u2019s Enthralling Voice by Dharitri Kumar Dasgupta, Vedanta Kesari March 2010, page 27, published by Ramakrishna Math, Chennai</ref> She was deeply impressed and thereby began to cultivate a relationship which would be long lasting and significant for her.<ref>Swami Vivekananda's Spiritual Mind by Swami Atmarupananda, Prabuddha Bharat (Awakened India), January 2009, page 20, published by Advaita Ashrama, Mayawati</ref>\n\nMacLeod became a member of the Vedanta Society established by Vivekananda and pursued the study and practice of Vedanta. This interaction gave her a different perspective of living in \"eternity.\"{{sfn|Gallagher|Ashcraft|2006|p=10}} <!-- On this aspect of her ability, - this doesn't make sense with previous sentence -->Vivekananda noted \"I simply adore Joe (Josephine MacLeod) in her tact and quiet way. She is a feminine statesman or woman. She can wield a kingdom. I have seldom seen such strong yet good common sense in a human being.\"<ref name=Tantine>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vedanta.com/store/product723.html|title= Tantine: The Life and Times of Josephine MacLeod|accessdate=6 September 2013|publisher=Vedanta:Press and catalogue}}</ref> Josephine considered the propagation of Swamiji's message of Indian spirituality in the West as a responsibility.<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\" />\n[[File:Swami Vivekananda image London 1896.jpg|thumb|Swami Vivekananda in London in 1896.]]\nJosephine was 35 years old when she met Swamiji. She considered the day she met Vivekananda for the first time, 29 January 1895, to be her \"spiritual birthday\". She said, \"It is the Truth that I saw in Swamiji that has set me free; it was to set me free that Swamiji came.\"{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}} As a result of her constant interaction with Vivekananda during his lectures on Vedanta, her devotion to his teachings became so profound that she believed that he was the \"New Buddha\" and even called him \"Our Prophet.\"{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}}\n\nJosephine did not like anyone addressing her as Vivekananda's disciple; she would immediately retort that she was his friend. Her niece, later Lady Sandwich, remarked that she was not Swami's friend but \"''Him''\". Vivekananda held her in great esteem and would write to her on his inner feelings, which he did not share with anyone else, including the brother monks or his \"[[Alasinga Perumal|Madras Boys]]\". He noted in one letter that \"I can't even in imagination pay the immense debt of gratitude I owe you.\"{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}} On issues of conflict between the [[British Raj|British]] in India and the [[Belur Math]] in Calcutta, she intervened with officials in the [[British Government]] in [[England]] to resolve the issues.<ref name=Tantine/>\n\nWhen she was in London when Vivekananda was also lecturing there in 1896, the best fruit of every season was delivered to him from an anonymous person. The firm of William Whitley, a popular fruit dealer in London had been paid for such delivery by an anonymous benefactor. Pineapple, a rare fruit in London which was valued at a quarter per fruit, was delivered to him every day. The benefactor was thought to be Josephine, as she was in London when the fruit delivery started.{{sfn|Samkara|2011|p=88}}\n\nShe defended Vivekananda's religious ethos when, during her visit to India with him, she stated that \"our Swamiji's great exposition of [[Vedanta|Vedanta Philosophy]] always favoured than denied the mission of Christ, and left Christians better Christians...\"{{sfn|Sharma|1988|p=102}} Because Josephine's efforts in the US and the West were so strong, Swamiji named her a \"lady missionary\" of the [[Ramakrishna Order]] promoted by Vivekananda.{{sfn|Sharma|1988|p=102}}\n\nMs. MacLeod had asked Swmi Vivekananda if she would accompany him to India. His response was, \"Yes, come, if you want filth and degradation and poverty and many loin cloths talking religion. Don't come if you want anything else. We cannot bear one more criticism.\"<ref>Nivedita, The Dedicated, by Reymond, Lizelle, page 70, published by the John Day Co. 1953, {{ISBN|0910261164}}></ref> She came to India and on being asked what she could do for him (Swami Vivekananda), the latter replied gravely, \"Love India.\"<ref>\"Reminiscences of Swami Vivekananda by Josephine Macleod\"</ref>\n\n[[File:Swami Vivekananda September 1899 Ridgely Manner New York.jpg|thumb|Sitting (left to right): Swami Vivekananda, Alberta Sturges, Besse Leggett (hidden), Josephine MacLeod]]\n\nRecalling the Swami\u2019s lecture on the [[Bhagavad gita]], the foremost of the Hindu scriptures, sometime in 1895, she was quoted as saying, later: ''I saw with these very eyes (she pointed to her own eyes) [[Krishna]] himself standing there and preaching the Gita. That was my first wonderful vision. I stared and stared. . . .I saw only the figure and all else vanished''.<ref>Pravrajika Prabuddhaprana, The Life of Josephine MacLeod: Friend of Swami Vivekananda (Dakshineshwar: Sri Sarada Math, 1990), p. 12</ref>\nIn 1898 she visited India and traveled with Swami Vivekananda to North India including Almora, Kashmir and parts of Punjab. When in India she used to stay in [[Belur Math]], in the old house along with Mrs. [[Sara Bull]].<ref>Nivedita, The Dedicated, by Reymond, Lizelle, page 69, published by the John Day Co. 1953, {{ISBN|0910261164}}</ref>\nShe took every possible care of the Swami when he arrived in New York for the second time in 1899 while he stayed in Ridgely Manor or elsewhere in the America.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/fr/2006/08/04/stories/2006080400140300.htm] A place dear to Swami Vivekananda: Article in The Hindu</ref>\n[[Capt. Sevier]], who, along with his wife Mrs. [[Charlotte Sevier]] became disciple of Swami Vivekananda after attending the latter's lectures in London and who established the [[Advaita Ashrama]] in Mayawati, had consulted first Miss Macleod on her impression about Vivekananda<ref>Vivekananda, a biography, by Swami Nikhilananda, published by Advaita Ashrama, 1982, {{ISBN|0-911206-09-4}}</ref>\nIn 1900, Ms. Macleod traveled with Swami Vivekananda when the latter visited Paris to participate in the Congress of History of Religions, accompanied by Madame [[Emma Calve]], P\u00e8re Hyacynthe and Jules Bois. The team traveled through south West Europe to Constantinople, Athens, and finally to Cairo from where Swami returned to India.<ref>Swamiji and Emma Calve by Swami Tathagatananda, Vedanta Kesari, March 2010, published by Ramakrishna Math, Mylapore, Chennai [http://www.chennaimath.org/edownloads/emagazines/vedanta-kesari] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821115313/http://www.chennaimath.org/edownloads/emagazines/vedanta-kesari |date=2010-08-21 }} Vedanta Kesari in Chennai Math website</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nFollowing Vivekananda's death in 1902, she went into a depression for two years, after which she devoted the next four decades to the cause of promoting the Vedantic ethos of the Swamiji.<ref name=Tantine/> In his last letter to her, Vivekenanda wrote, \"You have been a good angel to me\".<ref name=Six/> In a previous letter, he had written, \"and to you, dear Joe, [[Pranam]]s.\"<ref name=Six>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ramakrishna.de/vidyatmananda/Chapter6.php|title=Chapter Six:The Devotee as Friend of Swami Vivekananda para 2|accessdate=6 September 2013|publisher= Ramakrishna.de}}</ref> Even after the death of Vivekananda, Josephine remained in touch with the Ramakrishna Order and often visited the Belur Math headquarters of the Order and stayed for many days.<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\" />\n\nJosephine was also very close to [[Sister Nivedita]], the disciple of Swami Vivekananda who dedicated her life towards education of Indian women and towards the cause of revival of Indian Nationalism.<ref>Nivedita, The Dedicated, by Reymond, Lizelle, page 168, published by the John Day Co. 1953, {{ISBN|0910261164}}</ref> She travelled to Japan and introduced Kakuso Okakura, the painter and artist and Prince Oda, a Buddhist Abbot, to Vivekananda.<ref>Nivedita, The Dedicated, by Reymond, Lizelle, page 243, published by the John Day Co. 1953, {{ISBN|0910261164}}</ref>\n\nShe provided the initial funding of $800 for the establishment of Udbodhan press, which was used to publish the [[Udbodhan]] Patrika, monthly Bengali magazine of the Ramakrishna Order.<ref>Nivedita O Rabindranath by Debanjan Sengupta, publisher Deys, Calcutta, {{ISBN|9788189834036}}</ref>\n\nJosephine Macleod also helped [[Ramakrishna Mission]] in tiding over political crises. In December 1916 Lord Carmichael, the then Lt-Governor of Bengal, made a statement casting aspersions on [[Ramakrishna Mission]]. [[Ramakrishna Math]] and Mission was always under close surveillance of the Government because of the alleged involvement of some of its monks in nationalist activities like involvement with the [[Anushilan Samity]] during the [[Partition of Bengal (1905)|Partition of Bengal]] before they renounced the world, and also because Swami Vivekananda's fiery speeches and ideals inspired many freedom fighters like [[Aurobindo Ghosh]]. [[Swami Saradananda]], the Secretary of [[Ramakrishna Mission]], under the advice of the Holy Mother [[Sri Sarada Devi]], met the Governor who subsequently retracted his statement. However Ramakrishna Mission was helped by the contacts at the high level that Josephine Macleod had, to form a favorable opinion in the Government circle.<ref>[http://www.eng.vedanta.ru/library/prabuddha_bharata/motherhodd_of_God_oct2004.php] Vedanta Russia</ref>\n\nShe also persuaded [[Swami Nityatmananda]], a close associate of [[Mahendranath Gupta]] or M, the author of [[The Gospel of Sri Ramakrishna]], to publish the viewpoints of M on Swami Vivekananda, which later appeared in the fifth volume of the Ramakrishna Kathamrita, the original Bengali version of the Gospel, as an appendix.<ref>Mahendra Nath Gupta (M.)\nThe Recorder of the Gospel of Sri Ramakrishna, by Swami Chetanananda, Vedanta Society of St. Louis, {{ISBN|978-091635694-1}}</ref>\n\nShe was in touch with many contemporary luminaries including [[George Bernard Shaw]] and [[Romain Rolland]]. She helped extensively in spreading the message of Vedanta and Swami Vivekananda's teachings in particular in various European languages including German. She also worked extensively for the cause of advancement of education of women in India, through her regular financial contribution to the school found and run by [[Sister Nivedita]].<ref name=\"People who knew Vivekananda - Josephine Macleod\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.vivekananda.net/pplheknew/svdisciples/JosephineMcCleod.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-10-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918021529/http://www.vivekananda.net/pplheknew/SVDisciples/JosephineMcCleod.html |archivedate=2012-09-18 }} A tribute to Vivekananda by Frank Paralato Jr.</ref>\n\nFrench scholar & Nobel Laurate [[Romain Rolland]] wrote of Josephine Macleod \"(She) never tires of pointing out his (Vivekananda\u2019s) beauty, his charm, the power of attraction which was radiating from him.\"<ref>R. Rolland, \"Journal 1915-1943,\" Inde (1960), quoted in \"People who knew Vivekananda - Josephine Macleod\"</ref>\n\nShe helped in conducting the first centenary celebration of the birth of [[Sri Ramakrishna]] in Calcutta in 1937.<ref>Global Vedanta, fall 2010 vol. xv, no. 4, published by Vedanta Society of Western Washington</ref>\n\nEven though closely affiliated with an organization which took a leading role in Hindu renaissance, she remained a Christian in faith. In her own words, she had become a better Christian through the influence of Vivekananda.<ref>Vedanta Kesari, March 2010, Ramakrishna Math, Mylapore, Chennai</ref>\n\nJosephine died in California in the autumn of 1949. At the time of her death, she was living at the [[Vedanta Society of Southern California]]'s center in [[Hollywood]].<ref name=Six/>\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last= Badrinath |first=Chaturvedi |title=Swami Vivekananda, the Living Vedanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qo1X96E0JPAC&pg=PA277|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-306209-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1= Gallagher |first1=Eugene V. |last2= Ashcraft |first2=W. Michael |title=Introduction to New and Alternative Religions in America: African diaspora traditions and other American innovations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ClaySHbUEogC&pg=RA3-PA9|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-98717-6|pages=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Samkara|first= Samkara|title=The Monk as Man: The Unknown Life of Swami Vivekananda|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TfP5kBxkZaAC&pg=PA88|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-310119-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Sil|first=Narasingha Prosad |title=Swami Vivekananda: A Reassessment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pTDPlJPyV_MC&pg=PA187|year=1997|publisher=Susquehanna University Press|isbn=978-0-945636-97-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Sharma |first=Arvind |title=Neo-Hindu Views of Christianity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wmJfXtWEzCkC&pg=PA102|year=1988|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-08791-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Vivekananda|first=Swami |title=Awakened India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W7koAAAAYAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Swami Smaranananda|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ramakrishnavivekananda.info/reminiscences/228_jm.htm Reminiscenses of Swami Vivekananda]\n\n== Books ==\n\n* Tantine: The Life and Times of Josephine MacLeod, by Pravrajika Prabhuddhaprana\n* Josephine Macleod And Vivekananda's Mission, by Linda Prugh, publisher Sri Ramakrishna Math, Chennai, {{ISBN|8171208517}}\n* Swami Vivekananda in the West: New Discoveries \u2013 By Marie Louise Burke (Advaita Ashrama, Kolkata)\n* Letters of Sister Nivedita \u2013 Edited by Prof. Sankari Prasad Basu (Nababharat Publishers, Calcutta, April 1982)\n\n{{Swami Vivekananda}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MacLeod, Josephine}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:Disciples and friends of Swami Vivekananda]]\n[[Category:Vedanta]]\n[[Category:Ramakrishna Mission]]\n[[Category:Ramakrishna]]\n[[Category:Neo-Vedanta]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Josephine MacLeod\n| image = Olea Bull, Betty Laggett and Josephine MacLeod July 1906.png\n| caption = Olea Bull, Betty Leggett and Josephine MacLeod at the Holdts Hotel, Bergon, Norway after dinner with King Haarkon and Queen Maud on July 23, 1906\n| birth_name = Josephine MacLeod\n| birth_date = 1858\n| birth_place =  United States\n| residence =[[New York City]]\n| death_date = 1949\n| death_place = [[Hollywood, California]] \n| occupation =  Religious activist\n| nationality = American\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| yearsactive= 1895\u20131949\n| othername = Joe<br> Jo-Jo<br> Yum<br> Tantine\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Josephine MacLeod''' (1858\u20131949) was an American friend and devotee of [[Swami Vivekananda]].<ref name=\"Studies2001\">{{cite book|author=Punjabi University. Dept. of Religious Studies|title=Journal of Religious Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P-snAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=11 October 2012|year=2001|publisher=Dept. of Religious Studies, Punjabi University.}}</ref>{{sfn|Sil|1997|p=187}} She had a strong attachment to India and was an active participant in the Ramakrishna Vivekananda movement.<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vivekananda.net/pplheknew/svdisciples/JosephineMcCleod.html |title=Josephine MacLeod \u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda |accessdate=11 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918021529/http://www.vivekananda.net/pplheknew/SVDisciples/JosephineMcCleod.html |archivedate=18 September 2012 }}</ref>\nShe was given the nicknames \"Tantine\" and \"Jo Jo\" by Vivekananda. She considered Swami Vivekananda to be her friend and helped him with his finances. She and [[Sister Nivedita]] exchanged letters discussing their positive impressions of Swami Vivekananda and they competed with each other for his attention.{{sfn|Sil|1997|p=187}}{{better source needed|date=August 2018}}\nJosephine was not a [[sanyasin]], unlike many others such as [[Sister Nivedita]] or [[Sister Christine]].<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\"/> She was instrumental in spreading Vivekananda's message on Vedanta in the West.{{sfn|Vivekananda|2000|p=110}}\nShe had many contributions to the initial and the later phases of the development of the order of [[Ramakrishna]] and [[Vivekananda]]. She was a contributor to many causes espoused by [[Sister Nivedita]], the most famous disciple of Vivekananda, including that of contributing financially towards the development of [[Indian National Movement]] esp. in Bengal and elsewhere in India.<ref>''Nivedita Lokmata'', By Sankari Prasad Basu, Publisher Ananda Publishers Pvt. Limited, 1968, {{ISBN|9788170669722}}</ref>\n[[File:Josephinemcleod.jpg|thumb|Josephine Macleod in 1939]]\n\n== Life ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nJosephine was born in 1858 to John David MacLeod and Mary Ann Lennon. Josephine's father was an American of Scottish descent. Her native place was Chicago. The couple had three sons and three daughters. Two of their daughters, Besse or Betty (1852\u20141931) and Josephine (1858\u20141949), became disciples of Swami Vivekananda.<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\" />  Betty married Mr. William Sturges of Chicago in the year 1876, and had a son named Hollister and a daughter named Alberta, who were also intimately connected with the [[Vedanta]] Societies and [[Ramakrishna]] order. Being unmarried herself, Josephine stayed with Betty and her family. After the death of William Sturges in 1894, Betty married Mr. Francis Legett, a businessman of New York, in 1895. [[Swami Vivekananda]] attended this marriage in Paris. [[Ridgely Manor]], which later became famous as one of the places to accommodate [[Swami Vivekananda]] during his travel to Americas and Europe in 1899, belonged to the Legett family.<ref>[http://ridgely.org/?p=276] Ridgely Manor Website</ref>\nJosephine was known by several other nicknames, including Joe, Jo-Jo, Yum and Tantine (meaning \"Aunty\"<ref name=Tantine/>).{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}}\n\n=== Relationship to Swami Vivekananda ===\nJosephine and her sister Betty first heard Swami Vivekananda's lecture on Vedanta philosophy in [[New York City]] on 29 January 1895. Their friend R. Dora Roetheslesberger had told them about Vivekananda. They had assembled in the sitting room of Vivekananda's apartment along with many other women and a few men. His lecture impressed her and she observed at the end of the lecture that the way he presented truth was something unique.<!-- suggest direct quote here --> She heard his lectures several times over the next seven years<!--  and she was always impacted by the way he presented the truth -->.{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}} \nThe meeting with Swami Vivekananda and her association with him for the remaining periods of his life in America and India was the most important event in her life according to her.<ref name=\"Vivekananda Enthralling\">Vivekananda\u2019s Enthralling Voice by Dharitri Kumar Dasgupta, Vedanta Kesari March 2010, page 27, published by Ramakrishna Math, Chennai</ref> She was deeply impressed and thereby began to cultivate a relationship which would be long lasting and significant for her.<ref>Swami Vivekananda's Spiritual Mind by Swami Atmarupananda, Prabuddha Bharat (Awakened India), January 2009, page 20, published by Advaita Ashrama, Mayawati</ref>\n\nMacLeod became a member of the Vedanta Society established by Vivekananda and pursued the study and practice of Vedanta. This interaction gave her a different perspective of living in \"eternity.\"{{sfn|Gallagher|Ashcraft|2006|p=10}} <!-- On this aspect of her ability, - this doesn't make sense with previous sentence -->Vivekananda noted \"I simply adore Joe (Josephine MacLeod) in her tact and quiet way. She is a feminine statesman or woman. She can wield a kingdom. I have seldom seen such strong yet good common sense in a human being.\"<ref name=Tantine>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vedanta.com/store/product723.html|title= Tantine: The Life and Times of Josephine MacLeod|accessdate=6 September 2013|publisher=Vedanta:Press and catalogue}}</ref> Josephine considered the propagation of Swamiji's message of Indian spirituality in the West as a responsibility.<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\" />\n[[File:Swami Vivekananda image London 1896.jpg|thumb|Swami Vivekananda in London in 1896.]]\nJosephine was 35 years old when she met Swamiji. She considered the day she met Vivekananda for the first time, 29 January 1895, to be her \"spiritual birthday\". She said, \"It is the Truth that I saw in Swamiji that has set me free; it was to set me free that Swamiji came.\"{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}} As a result of her constant interaction with Vivekananda during his lectures on Vedanta, her devotion to his teachings became so profound that she believed that he was the \"New Buddha\" and even called him \"Our Prophet.\"{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}}\n\nJosephine did not like anyone addressing her as Vivekananda's disciple; she would immediately retort that she was his friend. Her niece, later Lady Sandwich, remarked that she was not Swami's friend but \"''Him''\". Vivekananda held her in great esteem and would write to her on his inner feelings, which he did not share with anyone else, including the brother monks or his \"[[Alasinga Perumal|Madras Boys]]\". He noted in one letter that \"I can't even in imagination pay the immense debt of gratitude I owe you.\"{{sfn|Badrinath|2006|p=277}} On issues of conflict between the [[British Raj|British]] in India and the [[Belur Math]] in Calcutta, she intervened with officials in the [[British Government]] in [[England]] to resolve the issues.<ref name=Tantine/>\n\nWhen she was in London when Vivekananda was also lecturing there in 1896, the best fruit of every season was delivered to him from an anonymous person. The firm of William Whitley, a popular fruit dealer in London had been paid for such delivery by an anonymous benefactor. Pineapple, a rare fruit in London which was valued at a quarter per fruit, was delivered to him every day. The benefactor was thought to be Josephine, as she was in London when the fruit delivery started.{{sfn|Samkara|2011|p=88}}\n\nShe defended Vivekananda's religious ethos when, during her visit to India with him, she stated that \"our Swamiji's great exposition of [[Vedanta|Vedanta Philosophy]] always favoured than denied the mission of Christ, and left Christians better Christians...\"{{sfn|Sharma|1988|p=102}} Because Josephine's efforts in the US and the West were so strong, Swamiji named her a \"lady missionary\" of the [[Ramakrishna Order]] promoted by Vivekananda.{{sfn|Sharma|1988|p=102}}\n\nMs. MacLeod had asked Swmi Vivekananda if she would accompany him to India. His response was, \"Yes, come, if you want filth and degradation and poverty and many loin cloths talking religion. Don't come if you want anything else. We cannot bear one more criticism.\"<ref>Nivedita, The Dedicated, by Reymond, Lizelle, page 70, published by the John Day Co. 1953, {{ISBN|0910261164}}></ref> She came to India and on being asked what she could do for him (Swami Vivekananda), the latter replied gravely, \"Love India.\"<ref>\"Reminiscences of Swami Vivekananda by Josephine Macleod\"</ref>\n\n[[File:Swami Vivekananda September 1899 Ridgely Manner New York.jpg|thumb|Sitting (left to right): Swami Vivekananda, Alberta Sturges, Besse Leggett (hidden), Josephine MacLeod]]\n\nRecalling the Swami\u2019s lecture on the [[Bhagavad gita]], the foremost of the Hindu scriptures, sometime in 1895, she was quoted as saying, later: ''I saw with these very eyes (she pointed to her own eyes) [[Krishna]] himself standing there and preaching the Gita. That was my first wonderful vision. I stared and stared. . . .I saw only the figure and all else vanished''.<ref>Pravrajika Prabuddhaprana, The Life of Josephine MacLeod: Friend of Swami Vivekananda (Dakshineshwar: Sri Sarada Math, 1990), p. 12</ref>\nIn 1898 she visited India and traveled with Swami Vivekananda to North India including Almora, Kashmir and parts of Punjab. When in India she used to stay in [[Belur Math]], in the old house along with Mrs. [[Sara Bull]].<ref>Nivedita, The Dedicated, by Reymond, Lizelle, page 69, published by the John Day Co. 1953, {{ISBN|0910261164}}</ref>\nShe took every possible care of the Swami when he arrived in New York for the second time in 1899 while he stayed in Ridgely Manor or elsewhere in the America.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/fr/2006/08/04/stories/2006080400140300.htm] A place dear to Swami Vivekananda: Article in The Hindu</ref>\n[[Capt. Sevier]], who, along with his wife Mrs. [[Charlotte Sevier]] became disciple of Swami Vivekananda after attending the latter's lectures in London and who established the [[Advaita Ashrama]] in Mayawati, had consulted first Miss Macleod on her impression about Vivekananda<ref>Vivekananda, a biography, by Swami Nikhilananda, published by Advaita Ashrama, 1982, {{ISBN|0-911206-09-4}}</ref>\nIn 1900, Ms. Macleod traveled with Swami Vivekananda when the latter visited Paris to participate in the Congress of History of Religions, accompanied by Madame [[Emma Calve]], P\u00e8re Hyacynthe and Jules Bois. The team traveled through south West Europe to Constantinople, Athens, and finally to Cairo from where Swami returned to India.<ref>Swamiji and Emma Calve by Swami Tathagatananda, Vedanta Kesari, March 2010, published by Ramakrishna Math, Mylapore, Chennai [http://www.chennaimath.org/edownloads/emagazines/vedanta-kesari] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821115313/http://www.chennaimath.org/edownloads/emagazines/vedanta-kesari |date=2010-08-21 }} Vedanta Kesari in Chennai Math website</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nFollowing Vivekananda's death in 1902, she went into a depression for two years, after which she devoted the next four decades to the cause of promoting the Vedantic ethos of the Swamiji.<ref name=Tantine/> In his last letter to her, Vivekenanda wrote, \"You have been a good angel to me\".<ref name=Six/> In a previous letter, he had written, \"and to you, dear Joe, [[Pranam]]s.\"<ref name=Six>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ramakrishna.de/vidyatmananda/Chapter6.php|title=Chapter Six:The Devotee as Friend of Swami Vivekananda para 2|accessdate=6 September 2013|publisher= Ramakrishna.de}}</ref> Even after the death of Vivekananda, Josephine remained in touch with the Ramakrishna Order and often visited the Belur Math headquarters of the Order and stayed for many days.<ref name=\"Josephine MacLeod\u2013 Disciple of Swami Vivekananda\" />\n\nJosephine was also very close to [[Sister Nivedita]], the disciple of Swami Vivekananda who dedicated her life towards education of Indian women and towards the cause of revival of Indian Nationalism.<ref>Nivedita, The Dedicated, by Reymond, Lizelle, page 168, published by the John Day Co. 1953, {{ISBN|0910261164}}</ref> She travelled to Japan and introduced Kakuso Okakura, the painter and artist and Prince Oda, a Buddhist Abbot, to Vivekananda.<ref>Nivedita, The Dedicated, by Reymond, Lizelle, page 243, published by the John Day Co. 1953, {{ISBN|0910261164}}</ref>\n\nShe provided the initial funding of $800 for the establishment of Udbodhan press, which was used to publish the [[Udbodhan]] Patrika, monthly Bengali magazine of the Ramakrishna Order.<ref>Nivedita O Rabindranath by Debanjan Sengupta, publisher Deys, Calcutta, {{ISBN|9788189834036}}</ref>\n\nJosephine Macleod also helped [[Ramakrishna Mission]] in tiding over political crises. In December 1916 Lord Carmichael, the then Lt-Governor of Bengal, made a statement casting aspersions on [[Ramakrishna Mission]]. [[Ramakrishna Math]] and Mission was always under close surveillance of the Government because of the alleged involvement of some of its monks in terrorist activities like involvement with the [[Anushilan Samity]] during the [[Partition of Bengal (1905)|Partition of Bengal]] before they renounced the world, and also because Swami Vivekananda's fiery speeches and ideals inspired many freedom fighters like [[Aurobindo Ghosh]]. [[Swami Saradananda]], the Secretary of [[Ramakrishna Mission]], under the advice of the Holy Mother [[Sri Sarada Devi]], met the Governor who subsequently retracted his statement. However Ramakrishna Mission was helped by the contacts at the high level that Josephine Macleod had, to form a favorable opinion in the Government circle.<ref>[http://www.eng.vedanta.ru/library/prabuddha_bharata/motherhodd_of_God_oct2004.php] Vedanta Russia</ref>\n\nShe also persuaded [[Swami Nityatmananda]], a close associate of [[Mahendranath Gupta]] or M, the author of [[The Gospel of Sri Ramakrishna]], to publish the viewpoints of M on Swami Vivekananda, which later appeared in the fifth volume of the Ramakrishna Kathamrita, the original Bengali version of the Gospel, as an appendix.<ref>Mahendra Nath Gupta (M.)\nThe Recorder of the Gospel of Sri Ramakrishna, by Swami Chetanananda, Vedanta Society of St. Louis, {{ISBN|978-091635694-1}}</ref>\n\nShe was in touch with many contemporary luminaries including [[George Bernard Shaw]] and [[Romain Rolland]]. She helped extensively in spreading the message of Vedanta and Swami Vivekananda's teachings in particular in various European languages including German. She also worked extensively for the cause of advancement of education of women in India, through her regular financial contribution to the school found and run by [[Sister Nivedita]].<ref name=\"People who knew Vivekananda - Josephine Macleod\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.vivekananda.net/pplheknew/svdisciples/JosephineMcCleod.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-10-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918021529/http://www.vivekananda.net/pplheknew/SVDisciples/JosephineMcCleod.html |archivedate=2012-09-18 }} A tribute to Vivekananda by Frank Paralato Jr.</ref>\n\nFrench scholar & Nobel Laurate [[Romain Rolland]] wrote of Josephine Macleod \"(She) never tires of pointing out his (Vivekananda\u2019s) beauty, his charm, the power of attraction which was radiating from him.\"<ref>R. Rolland, \"Journal 1915-1943,\" Inde (1960), quoted in \"People who knew Vivekananda - Josephine Macleod\"</ref>\n\nShe helped in conducting the first centenary celebration of the birth of [[Sri Ramakrishna]] in Calcutta in 1937.<ref>Global Vedanta, fall 2010 vol. xv, no. 4, published by Vedanta Society of Western Washington</ref>\n\nEven though closely affiliated with an organization which took a leading role in Hindu renaissance, she remained a Christian in faith. In her own words, she had become a better Christian through the influence of Vivekananda.<ref>Vedanta Kesari, March 2010, Ramakrishna Math, Mylapore, Chennai</ref>\n\nJosephine died in California in the autumn of 1949. At the time of her death, she was living at the [[Vedanta Society of Southern California]]'s center in [[Hollywood]].<ref name=Six/>\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last= Badrinath |first=Chaturvedi |title=Swami Vivekananda, the Living Vedanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qo1X96E0JPAC&pg=PA277|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-306209-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1= Gallagher |first1=Eugene V. |last2= Ashcraft |first2=W. Michael |title=Introduction to New and Alternative Religions in America: African diaspora traditions and other American innovations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ClaySHbUEogC&pg=RA3-PA9|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-98717-6|pages=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Samkara|first= Samkara|title=The Monk as Man: The Unknown Life of Swami Vivekananda|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TfP5kBxkZaAC&pg=PA88|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-310119-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Sil|first=Narasingha Prosad |title=Swami Vivekananda: A Reassessment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pTDPlJPyV_MC&pg=PA187|year=1997|publisher=Susquehanna University Press|isbn=978-0-945636-97-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Sharma |first=Arvind |title=Neo-Hindu Views of Christianity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wmJfXtWEzCkC&pg=PA102|year=1988|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-08791-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Vivekananda|first=Swami |title=Awakened India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W7koAAAAYAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Swami Smaranananda|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ramakrishnavivekananda.info/reminiscences/228_jm.htm Reminiscenses of Swami Vivekananda]\n\n== Books ==\n\n* Tantine: The Life and Times of Josephine MacLeod, by Pravrajika Prabhuddhaprana\n* Josephine Macleod And Vivekananda's Mission, by Linda Prugh, publisher Sri Ramakrishna Math, Chennai, {{ISBN|8171208517}}\n* Swami Vivekananda in the West: New Discoveries \u2013 By Marie Louise Burke (Advaita Ashrama, Kolkata)\n* Letters of Sister Nivedita \u2013 Edited by Prof. Sankari Prasad Basu (Nababharat Publishers, Calcutta, April 1982)\n\n{{Swami Vivekananda}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MacLeod, Josephine}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:Disciples and friends of Swami Vivekananda]]\n[[Category:Vedanta]]\n[[Category:Ramakrishna Mission]]\n[[Category:Ramakrishna]]\n[[Category:Neo-Vedanta]]\n", "name_user": "A Seeker of Truth", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josephine_MacLeod"}
{"title_page": "Chuck Wilson (pilot)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|US Air Force officer and pilot}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name         = Chuck Wilson\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1953|11|22}}\n|birth_place  = [[Indianapolis, Indiana]], US\n|image        = Colonel CP Wilson II May 2005 Memorial Day Ceremony.jpg\n|caption      = Wilson at a [[Memorial Day]] ceremony in May 2005\n|nickname     = Chuck\n|allegiance   = United States\n|branch       = United States Air Force\n|serviceyears = 1977\u20132004 (27 years)\n|rank         = [[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|25px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n|commands     = {{ubl\n                |6510th ABG HQ Sq\n                |4402nd RS\n                |[[5th Reconnaissance Squadron|5th RS]]\n                |[[505th Command and Control Wing|AFC2TIC/AFC2TIG]]\n                }}\n|battles      = {{ubl\n                |[[Cold War]]\n                |[[Gulf War]]\n                |[[Global war on terror]]\n                }}\n|awards       = {{ubl\n                |[[Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n                |[[Legion of Merit]]\n                |[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]]\n                }}\n|laterwork    = \n}}\n'''Charles Paul Wilson II''' (born November 22, 1953) is a retired United States Air Force [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] who is notable for his work in [[Bureau of Political-Military Affairs|political-military affairs]], [[National security of the United States|national security policy]], [[Military acquisition|defense acquisition]], and [[Business development|business development]]. He commanded four different military units at the [[Squadron (aviation)|squadron]] and [[Wing (military unit)|wing]] organizational levels. Wilson performed operational testing of the prototype S1034 [[pressure suit]] and flew the first operational mission of the [[Lockheed U-2]]S spy plane. He is a [[U.S. Air Force aeronautical rating#USAF rating requirements|rated]] US Air Force command pilot with over 3,800 flight hours.\n\nAfter retiring from the Air Force, Wilson worked as a business executive in the aerospace industry. He is a [[museum docent|docent]] at the [[National Air and Space Museum]], author, and a frequent military aviation speaker. Wilson is active in [[Veterans' affairs|veterans' affairs]] and has made significant contributions including serving in leadership roles of increasing responsibility.\n\n== Early life and education==\nWilson was born November 22, 1953, in Indianapolis, Indiana{{r|Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}} and was the first of three children born to Charles Wilson Sr. and Mary Wilson. He grew up in Indianapolis where his father was a [[World War II]] combat veteran and an engineer for [[General Motors Corporation]] and his mother was a homemaker.{{r|Obit Indy Star (2004)}} Wilson went to Saint Michael's Grade School and graduated from North Central High School. Wilson also graduated from [[Culver Military Academy]] summer schools. He earned a Bachelor of Science Degree from Indiana University (IU).{{r|Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}} While at IU, Wilson worked at United Parcel Service (UPS) at night unloading trucks, sorting packages, and was promoted into UPS management. Later, Wilson earned a Master of Science degree from [[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] (1985), graduated from the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College]], the [[Armed Forces Staff College]] (now the Joint Forces Staff College), the [[Air War College]], and was the 1997 National Defense [[Fellow]] and author of ''Strategic & Tactical Air Reconnaissance in the Near East.''{{r|Potomac Local (2019)}}{{r|Wilson (2012)}}{{r|Embry-Riddle (2019)}}\n\n== Military career ==\n[[File:Charles Wilson pilot of KC-135Q.jpg |left|thumb|Wilson at the controls of a KC{{nbh}}135Q Stratotanker]]\nDuring his freshman year at Indiana University, Wilson, entered the [[Air Force Reserve Officer Training Corps]] (AFROTC) as a pilot candidate and completed the Air Force flight instruction program with a [[private pilot license]]. With the drawdown of US forces in Vietnam, Air Force pilot production was minimized with AFROTC pilot candidate slots for active duty virtually eliminated.{{r|F-4 Society (2001)}} Instead, Wilson was commissioned a [[Second lieutenant#United_States|second lieutenant]], and in 1977, received orders to [[Port Austin Air Force Station]] in Michigan where he was posted as the chief of administration and personnel.{{r| Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}}\n\nIn 1980, Wilson was selected as commander of the 6510th Air Base Group (ABG) Headquarters Squadron, responsible for base services including personnel, public affairs, and security,{{r|AFFTC (1962)}} where he achieved the [[Air Force Flight Test Center]]'s \"Executive Officer of the Year\" award. Wilson was subsequently selected for [[Air Education and Training Command#Flying training|Undergraduate Pilot Training (UPT)]] at [[Reese Air Force Base]], Texas. After completing UPT, Wilson was assigned to fly the [[Boeing KC-135 Stratotanker|KC-135]]Q Stratotanker that refueled the [[Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird|SR-71 Blackbird]].{{r| Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}} The Q-model KC-135 aircraft was specially configured to dispense the [[JP-7]] fuel required by the SR-71.{{r|Graham (1996)}}\n\n===U-2 Dragon Lady===\n[[File:Wilson and Desert Dragons U-2S in 1994.jpg |right|thumb|Wilson in blue prototype S1034 suit with other pilots of the 4402nd RS at Taif Air Base in 1994]]\nIn 1986, Wilson was selected to fly the Lockheed U-2 ''Dragon Lady'', a high altitude reconnaissance aircraft. He served on many operational deployments in Europe, the Pacific, and Southwest Asia. Wilson advanced to [[flight instructor]] in the U-2 and in 1993 commanded the 4402nd Reconnaissance Squadron (Provisional), known as the ''Desert Dragons,'' at [[Taif Air Base]], Saudi Arabia.{{r| Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}}{{r|Jenkins (2012)|p=354}} A provisional squadron is one created for a limited time to accomplish a specific mission.{{r|Free Dictionary Provisional}} The 4402nd was formed to continue reconnaissance operations over Iraq after the end of the [[1991 Gulf War]] in order to ensure compliance with [[United Nations]] (UN) resolutions.{{r|Pocock (2005)|p=312}} U-2s from the 4402nd flew ''Olive Branch'' missions to provide imagery for the [[United Nations Special Commission]] (UNSCOM) that searched for evidence of Iraqi [[weapons of mass destruction]].{{r|Pocock (2005)|p=312}}{{r|Norris (2010)|p=178}} The Iraqi government did not approve of these [[Freedoms of the air#First_freedom|overflights]], and Wilson's first U-2 mission for the UN was targeted by Iraqi [[anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft weapons]]. The U-2s operating in-theater at this time had outdated defensive capabilities. Wilson's mission report was instrumental in obtaining funding for the \"Band Aid\" upgrades to the U-2's defensive systems.{{r|Pocock (2005)|p=313}} The U-2 flies at altitudes where the [[air pressure]] is too low for an unprotected person to survive. During his tour with the 4402nd, Wilson performed operational testing of the prototype S1034 pressure suit manufactured by the [[David Clark Company]] to evaluate its suitability in the U-2.{{r|Jenkins (2012)|p=354}}\n\n[[File:Lt. Colonel Charles P. Wilson II 5th RS Commander.jpg |right|thumb|5th RS Commander Wilson with Lockheed U-2 at Osan Air Base, South Korea in 1995]]\nIn 1995, Wilson was assigned command of the [[5th Reconnaissance Squadron]], known as the ''Blackcats'', that operated from [[Osan Air Base]], South Korea.{{r|Fact Sheet 5RS (2019)}} The squadron received the U-2S{{r|5RS Fact Sheet (2007)}} with an upgraded [[General Electric F118]]-101 engine that provided significant weight and fuel savings over the previous [[Pratt & Whitney J75]] engine.{{r|Pocock (2005)|p=315}}{{r|U-2S Fact Sheet (2015)}} On October 20, 1995, Wilson flew the first U-2S operational mission.{{r|5RS Fact Sheet (2007)}} Under Wilson's leadership, the 5th Reconnaissance Squadron received the 1995 Lockheed Advanced Development Corporation (Skunkworks) \"Hughes Trophy,\" distinguishing the unit as the best reconnaissance squadron in the [[9th Reconnaissance Wing]] that year. The 5th RS was also nominated for the [[Republic of Korea Presidential Unit Citation]].{{r|5RS Fact Sheet (2007)}}\n\nPromoted to colonel in 1997{{r|CY97 Colonels (1997)}}, Wilson was assigned as the commander of the [[Air Force Command and Control Training and Innovation Center]] (AFC2TIC) at [[Hurlburt Field]], Florida. The [[center of excellence]] was renamed as the [[Air Force Command and Control Training and Innovation Group]] (AFC2TIG) in April 1999 and renamed again in 2004 as the [[505th Command and Control Wing]]. Wilson's organization re-engineered airpower [[command and control]] (C<sup>2</sup>) at the operational level of war. [[Air Operations Center]]s worldwide were restructured with trained staff, standardized equipment, and worked with a deliberate process that is used across the globe.{{r|505 C&C Wing Fact Sheet (2012)}} The team trained warfighters of different experience levels. On short notice and at the direction of the [[Chief of Staff of the United States Air Force|chief of staff]], AFC2TIG trained every active duty Air Force general officer on the [[Theater Battle Management Core System]].{{r|AFC2TIG TBMCS (2001)}} Wilson led and managed this group of over 3,000 personnel and 13 disparate Air Force units located across the United States.{{r|AFC2TIG CC (2001)}}\n\n===Pentagon assignments===\nIn 1993, Wilson served on the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff#Joint Staff|Joint Staff]] of the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] (JCS) at the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] in Arlington, Virgina.{{r|Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}} During this time, review and approval for peacetime reconnaissance operations was performed using the JCS \"book process\" and coordinated by the Reconnaissance Operations Division (ROD) within the [[J3 Operations Directorate]].{{r|Santucci (2013)|pp=132-3}} As Chief of Air Reconnaissance Plans and Programs{{r| Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}}, also known as the \"book officer\", Wilson was the principle focal point for acquiring [[National Command Authority]] and [[National Security Council]] approval for sensitive reconnaissance missions worldwide. In this position, he was also the advisor to the United Nations for Airborne Reconnaissance.{{r|Santucci (2013)|pp=132-3}}\n\nIn 1997, Wilson was selected for the [[Office of the Secretary of Defense]] as the Chief of Manned Reconnaissance in the [[Defense Airborne Reconnaissance Office]] (DARO), and in 1998, Deputy Director for Airborne Intelligence Surveillance and Reconnaissance Programs in the Office of the Assistant Secretary of Defense (Command, Control, Communications and Intelligence), or ASD(C<sup>3</sup>I), to oversee defense acquisition of air reconnaissance systems.{{r|Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}} ASD(C<sup>3</sup>I) was replaced by the [[Assistant Secretary of Defense for Networks and Information Integration]], or ASD(NII) in May 2003.{{r|ASDC3I Replaced|p=20}}\n\n===Department of State===\n[[File:Franks-Wilson.jpg|left|thumb|ISO Director Wilson (right) escorting [[USCENTCOM]] Commander General [[Tommy Franks]] to the European Chiefs of Mission Conference in 2003]]\nIn 2001, Wilson transitioned to military roles that interacted with the Department of State. Assigned as the deputy director of the Office of Contingency Planning and Peacekeeping within the [[Bureau of Political-Military Affairs]], he was the senior Air Force advisor at the State Department. Shortly after the [[September 11 attacks]], Wilson was promoted to director of the Office of International Security Operations (ISO){{r|Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}} that provided the Department of Defense's primary interface with the Department of State on operational military situations.{{r|Tucker (2002)|p=24}} As ISO director, he was the senior US military representative to the Department of State.{{r|Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}} To support the [[24/7 service|around-the-clock]] war-time tempo, Wilson designed and implemented Political Military Action Teams (PMATs) that became the State Department's point of contact for military operations on the [[Global War on Terror]].{{r|Tucker (2002)|p=23}}{{r|PMAT (2002)}}\n\nWilson oversaw ISO activities that included obtaining clearances for US cargo aircraft to enter the [[airspace]] of other countries, refueling at foreign airports, coordinating diplomatic efforts to establish bases in the countries bordering Afghanistan, and eventually supporting US embassies efforts to base US forces in coalition nations.{{r|Tucker (2002)|p=24}}{{r|ISO Director (2002)}}\n\n[[File:Charles Wilson leading US Delegation during talks with UK about Diego Garcia.jpg|thumb|left|Wilson (in vest) leading the US delegation in the India Office Council Chamber within the [[UK Foreign Office]]]]\nIn 2002, Wilson led the US delegation in the annual United States/United Kingdom Political-Military talks to discuss access to the British-owned island of [[Diego Garcia]].{{r|Diego Garcia Talks (2002)}} Wilson and [[British Indian Ocean Territory]] commissioner, [[Alan Huckle]], reached agreement to add shelters for the [[B-2 Spirit]] bomber as well as upgrade existing infrastructure. B-2 facilities on Diego Garcia would allow the bombers to be based much closer to potential targets in the [[Asia-Pacific]] region reducing round-trip flight time from their Missouri bases from 50 hours to approximately 15.{{r|Sand (2009)}} Two of the B-2 shelters were completed at [[Naval Support Facility Diego Garcia]] by the end of 2002 and two additional shelters were added in 2005.<ref name=\"gs\">{{cite news |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/aircraft/systems/xldahs.htm |title=B-2 Shelter System [B2SS] Extra Large Deployable Aircraft Hangar Systems (Formerly: B-2 Shelter Program) |publisher=[[GlobalSecurity.org]] |archive-url=https://archive.li/bJAde |archive-date=April 14, 2013 |access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne of Wilson's priorities as ISO director was providing information to Defense and State leadership.{{r|ISO Functions (2002)}} This task required he and his staff support visits to the State Department by senior military officers.{{r|Tommy Franks (2003)}} These efforts were helpful and appreciated as demonstrated when USCENTCOM commander, General Franks, visited to personally meet and thank members of the ISO coalition team.{{r|Tucker (2002)|p=24}}\n\nWith 27 years of service, Wilson retired from the Air Force in December 2004 with over 3,800 flying hours in the [[Cessna T-37 Tweet|T-37]], [[Northrop T-38 Talon|T-38]], KC-135A, KC-135Q, TR-1, and U-2.{{r|USAF Wilson Bio (2004)}}\n\n==Later years==\nAfter retirement, Wilson worked in the aerospace industry at [[Raytheon]] as the senior corporate business development lead for air intelligence programs.{{r|VFW D10 Wilson Bio (2017)}} He also worked for [[L-3 Communications]]\u2019 [[Wescam|Wescam/Sonoma]] Electro Optic (EO) imaging systems as a director of business development for airborne intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance (ISR) sensors.{{r|VFW D10 Wilson Bio (2017)}} Wilson was also an aerospace consultant with the Goyak Group{{r|Potomac Local (2016)}} specializing in national security, foreign policy, and business development.{{r|PWL VFW All American (2018)}}\n\n[[File:Chuck Wilson Veterans Day Quantico VA 2019.jpg|thumb|right|Wilson at the [[Quantico National Cemetery]] [[Veterans Day]] ceremony in 2019]]\nWilson remains active in the aerospace community as a volunteer for a number of organizations. He is a [[Museum docent|docent]] and military aviation lecturer at the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] National Air and Space Museum's (NASM) [[Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center]] annex at [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] in Virginia.{{r|Potomac Local (2019)}} In 2016, he spoke at Freedom Museum in [[Manassas, Virginia]] about his USAF career as a U-2 pilot.{{r|Freedom Museum (2016)}} In 2017, Wilson appeared in the documentary, ''The Dragon Lady'', from the [[Smithsonian Channel]]\u2019s Air Warriors series of videos.{{r|Pocock (2017)}}{{r|Dragon Lady (2017)}} In 2019, he was elected chairman of [[The Cold War Museum]]\u2019s Board of Directors.{{r|Potomac Local (2019)}}{{r|Whats Up Woodbridge (2019)}}{{r|Fauquier Now (2019)}} Wilson is a member of the [[Order of Daedalians]]{{r|Daedalus Flyer (2017)}} and in 2019 served as [[Military chaplain|chaplain]] of Daedalian Flight 4, the National Capital Flight, in [[Fort Myer]], Virginia.{{r|Chaplain (2019)}}\n\nIn veterans' affairs, Wilson has served in increasingly responsible leadership roles. In 2015, Wilson commanded the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] (VFW) Hawkins-Reeve Post 7916{{r|VFW Wilson Bio (2015)}} where he was awarded \"All State\" and \"All American\" honors recognizing exceptional leadership and accomplishment in membership growth and participation in key programs.{{r|VFW D10 Wilson Bio (2017)}} On February 23, 2016, Wilson addressed the [[Senate of Virginia]] to stress the importance of House Bill 63 that would bring Virginia law in accordance with Federal law by exempting veteran service organizations from local taxation. House Bill 63 was approved by the Virginia assembly and signed into law by the governor.{{r|HB63 Passes (2016)}} Later in 2016, Wilson was elected chairman of the Potomac Region Veterans Council where he represented over 15,000 veterans in 29 veteran service organizations.{{r|Potomac Local (2016)}} In 2017, Wilson transitioned to commander of Virginia District 10,{{r|WUPW VFW Post 7916 (2017)}} where he again achieved \"All State\" and \"All American\" honors.{{r|VFW D10 Wilson Bio (2017)}}\n\n{{Asof|2015}}, Wilson and his wife, Judy, have four children and four grandchildren.{{r|VFW Wilson Bio (2015)}}\n\n===Awards and decorations===\nWilson was awarded the following decorations for his military service. Based on his assignments, he was also authorized to wear the [[Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge]] and [[Air Force Commander Badge]].{{r|Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}}{{r|USAF Wilson Bio (2004)}}\n\n{| align=\"center\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |[[File:COMMAND PILOT WINGS.png|200px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Superior Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}&nbsp;{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Meritorious Service_Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}&nbsp;{{ribbon devices|number=4|type=oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|name=Air Medal ribbon|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|name=Aerial Achievement Medal ribbon|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Air Force Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Joint Meritorious Unit Award-3d.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=5|type=oak|other_device=|ribbon=Outstanding Unit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Combat Readiness Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Korea Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Southwest Asia Service Medal ribbon (1991\u20132016).svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Humanitarian Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Air Force Overseas Short Tour Service Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=5|type=oak|ribbon=Air Force Longevity Service ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=USAF Marksmanship ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Air_Force_Training_Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n<!-- |colspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"|[[File:USAFCommanderBdg.jpg|106px]]  -->\n<!-- |colspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"|[[File:Office_of_the_Secretary_of_Defense_Identification_Badge.png|106px]]  -->\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|[[File:Joint_Chiefs_of_Staff_seal.svg|130px]]\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Badge\n|colspan=\"12\" align=\"center\" |[[USAF aeronautical rating#Pilot ratings|USAF Command pilot]]\n|-\n!Row 1\n|colspan=\"12\" align=\"center\" |[[Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n|-\n!Row 2\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Legion of Merit]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] w/ 4 [[oak leaf clusters]]\n|-\n!Row 3\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Air Medal]] w/ 1 [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Aerial Achievement Medal]] w/ 1 [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Air Force Commendation Medal]] w/ 1 [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|-\n!Row 4\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Air Force Outstanding Unit Award]] w/ a silver [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Combat Readiness Medal]] w/ 1 [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|-\n!Row 5\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[National Defense Service Medal]] w/ 1 [[service star]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Korea Defense Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]] w/ 2 [[service star]]s\n|-\n!Row 6\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Southwest Asia Service Medal]] w/ 1 [[service star]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Humanitarian Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Air Force Overseas Short Tour Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n!Row 7\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Air Force Longevity Service Award]] with a silver [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Marksmanship Ribbon#Air Force|Small Arms Expert Marksmanship Ribbon]] w/ 1 [[service star]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Air Force Training Ribbon]]\n|-\n!Badge\n<!-- |colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Air Force Commander's Insignia]]  -->\n<!-- |colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge]] -->\n|colspan=\"12\" align=\"center\" |[[Joint Chiefs of Staff Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Other achievements ===\nThe US Department of State twice selected him for the [[Superior Honor Award]] for leadership in the Global War on Terror, [[Operation Enduring Freedom]], and [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]]. The [[United Way]] honored Wilson twice with their \"Citizen of the Year\" award.{{r|Wilson DOS Bio (2004)}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|United States Air Force}}\n* [[4404th Wing (Provisional)]]\n* [[Black Cat Squadron]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"5RS Fact Sheet (2007)\">{{cite web |url= http://www.osan.af.mil/AboutUs/FactSheets/Display/tabid/4001/Article/404709/5th-reconnaissance-squadron.aspx |title= 5th Reconnaissance Squadron |date=February 26, 2007 |website= Osan Air Base |publisher= United States Air Force |access-date= February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"505 C&C Wing Fact Sheet (2012)\">{{cite web |url= https://www.afhra.af.mil/About-Us/Fact-Sheets/Display/Article/432129/505-command-and-control-wing-acc/ |title= 505 Command and Control Wing (ACC) |date=March 27, 2012 |website= Air Force Historical Research Agency |publisher= United States Air Force |access-date= February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AFC2TIG CC (2001)\">{{cite journal |url= |journal=Command and Control (C<sup>2</sup>) News  |title=Commander's Corner |date=Spring 2001 |v