)\">{{cite web |author= |url= http://whatsupwoodbridge.com/occoquan-vfw-post-7916-celebrates-new-leadership-honors-outgoing-commander/ |title= Occoquan VFW Post 7916 celebrates new leadership, honors outgoing Commander |publisher=What's Up Prince William |date= May 16, 2017 |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Attribution==\n:{{Air Force}}\n:{{Air Force Historical Research Agency}}\n:{{US DOS}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{cite web |title= 30th Anniversary Celebration of the Black Cats |url= http://www.blackbirds.net/u2/blackcats/blackcats-30-anniv.html |date=December 2, 2006 |publisher=Blackbirds.net |access-date=March 10, 2020}}\n* {{C-SPAN | charlespwilson}}\n* {{cite web |title= Blackbird Association Newsletter |date=March 2015 |url= http://members.habu.org/newsletter2015.pdf |publisher= Habu.org |location= |access-date=March 12, 2020}}\n* {{cite web |title=Colonel Charles P. Wilson II |url=https://www.blackbirds.net/u2/blackcats/cwilsonbio.html |date=March 25, 2004 |publisher=Blackbirds.net |access-date=February 7, 2020}}\n* {{cite web |last=Webster |first=Amanda |date=June 13, 2016 |title=Colonel Charles 'Chuck' Wilson to Speak at the Freedom Museum |url=https://www.pwar.com/colonel-charles-chuck-wilson-to-speak-at-the-freedom-museum/ |work=Realtor Association of Prince William |location=Woodbridge, Virginia |access-date=February 22, 2020}}\n* {{cite web |last=Wilson II |first=Charles P. |title= The Desert Dragons |date=November 28, 2016 |location= |url=https://www.slideshare.net/CharlesChuckWilson/the-desert-dragons |website=slideshare.net |publisher=LinkedIn Corporation |access-date=February 19, 2020}}\n* {{cite web |last=Wilson II |first=Charles P. |title= US-UK Bilateral Talks at DGAR Brief-1 |date=December 21, 2016 |location= |url= https://www.slideshare.net/CharlesChuckWilson/usuk-bilateral-talks-at-dgar-brief1-70339953 |website=slideshare.net |publisher=LinkedIn Corporation |access-date=March 17, 2020}}\n* {{cite web |last=Wilson II |first=Charles P. |date= |title= U-2 Mission |url= http://area51specialprojects.com/u2.html |website= area51specialprojects.com |location=|access-date=February 11,  2020}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Wilson II |first1=Charles P. |last2=McKinley |first2=James |date=April 12, 2005 |title= History of the Dragon Lady and the 5th Reconnaissance Squadron 'The Blackcats' |url= http://www.taiwanairpower.org/u2/blackcat.html |website= taiwanairpower.org |location= |access-date=February 19, 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson, Charles Paul, II}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Air War College alumni]]\n[[Category:American aviators]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University alumni]]\n[[Category:Joint Forces Staff College alumni]]\n[[Category:Indiana University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Writers from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Command and General Staff College alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Meritorious Service Medal (United States)]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chuck_Wilson_(pilot)"}
{"title_page": "The Red Dragon (magazine)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Welsh literary periodical (1882\u20131887)}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = The Red Dragon\n| logo            = \n| logo_size       = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_file      = The_Red_Dragon_periodical_cover_page_February_1882.jpg<!-- cover.jpg (omit the \"file:\" prefix) -->\n| image_size      = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_alt       =printed title page showing the magazine name in embellished script around a sketch of a dragon \n| image_caption   = Motto: {{Lang|cy|Y Ddraig Goch A Ddyry Gychwyn.}}<br/>\"The Red Dragon Will Lead The Way.\"\n| editor          = [[Charles Wilkins (writer)|Charles Wilkins]] 1882\u20131885\n| editor2         = James Harris 1885\u20131887<!-- up to |editor5= -->\n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| photographer    = \n| category        = Welsh history and literature\n| frequency       = Monthly\n| format          = \n| publisher       = Daniel Owen & Co. ([[Cardiff]], [[Wales]])\n| paid_circulation   = \n| unpaid_circulation = \n| total_circulation  = \n| founder         = Charles Wilkins\n| founded         = \n| firstdate       = February 1882<!-- {{Start date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| finaldate       = June 1887<!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| country         = Wales\n| language        = English\n| website         = [https://journals.library.wales/view/2062893/2062894/ The National Library of Wales: Welsh Journals]<!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''''The Red Dragon''''', '''''The National Magazine of Wales''''', was a monthly [[English language|English-language]] literary [[magazine]] published in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]], from February 1882 until June 1887 and edited by [[Charles Wilkins (writer)|Charles Wilkins]] until July 1885 when James Harris took over.\n\nAlthough directed primarily at the people of [[South Wales]], it was intended \"to make known to the greater English world the characteristics and aims of the Welsh people and the beauties of their language and literature\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4485019/4485021/14/|title=The End of Another National Venture|date=9 June 1887|work=Western Mail|url-status=live|page=2}}</ref> The magazine included articles on the [[history of Wales]] (emphasising its recent history), [[Biography|biographies]], [[poetry]] and [[serial novel]]s.\n\nThe closure of the magazine elicited numerous expressions of regret in local newspapers in 1887. ''The Red Dragon'' remains a useful historical resource for modern scholars as a record of traditional lore.\n\n== Background ==\nThe 1880s was a pivotal time of social change for Wales, especially in terms of the effects of [[industrialisation]] on traditional rural culture, language, religion, education, and politics. Three-quarters of the population spoke [[Welsh language|Welsh]] (though most not exclusively) but a [[Middle class|middle-class]] culture had developed that identified English with business and success.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last=Ballin|first=Malcolm|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2VeuBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA10|title=Welsh Periodicals in English: 1882\u20132012|publisher=University of Wales Press|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7083-2615-2|location=Cardiff|pages=10\u201322}}</ref> While there were \"articulate and powerful groups of business and professional Welshmen who congregated in London\",<ref>{{Cite book|last=Morgan|first=Kenneth O.|title=Rebirth of a Nation: A History of Modern Wales|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1981|isbn=|location=Oxford|page=6, cited in Ballin (2013), p. 11.|pages=}}</ref> Wales was considered by many British people to be little more than a picturesque relic of earlier times.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEnglish-language periodicals such as ''The Cambrian Register'' (1795\u201396, 1818),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.library.wales/view/2867877/2886559/|title=The Cambrian Register|website=The National Library of Wales: Welsh Journals|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> ''The Cambro-Britain and General Celtic Repository'' (1820\u20131822),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.library.wales/view/2000585/2000586/|title=The Cambro-Briton and General Celtic Repository|website=The National Library of Wales: Welsh Journals|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> ''[[Cambrian Quarterly Magazine and Celtic Repertory|The Cambrian Quarterly]]'' (1829\u20131833),<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://journals.library.wales/browse/2070008|title=The Cambrian Quarterly Magazine and Celtic Repertory|last=|first=|date=|website=The National Library of Wales: Welsh Journals|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> and ''The'' ''Cambrian Journal'' (1854\u20131864)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.library.wales/view/2072171/2072174/|title=The Cambrian Journal|website=The National Library of Wales: Welsh Journals|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> had intermittently attempted to promote Welsh learning, but had not lasted.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== History and content ==\nThe founding [[editor]] of ''The Red Dragon'' was historian and writer [[Charles Wilkins (writer)|Charles Wilkins]] who managed the magazine from February 1882 to June 1885.<ref name=\":0\" /> By that time, he was \"the most learned literary figure in Merthyr \u2013 and indeed in Wales\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Davies|first=John|title=A History of Wales|publisher=Penguin|year=2007|isbn=|location=London|page=375, cited by Ballin (2003), p. 11.|pages=}}</ref> Although born in England, he had lived most of his life in Merthyr Tydfil. He had already written histories of Merthyr and Wales and won a gold medal for his writing at the 1881 [[National Eisteddfod of Wales|National Eisteddfod]]. His [[bardic name]] was Catwg.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last={{lang|cy|Ap Ffarmwr}}|first=|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3273381/3273383/14/|title=Career of a Literary Postmaster|date=27 January 1898|work=Evening Express|access-date=|url-status=live|page=2}}</ref> Through ''The Red Dragon'', Wilkins intended to reach a growing public literate in English but with little knowledge of Wales<ref name=\":0\" /> and \"to make known to the greater English world the characteristics and aims of the Welsh people and the beauties of their language and literature\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nJames Harris took over the editorship in July 1885.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3364762/3364765/84/|title=The New Series of the National Magazine|date=4 July 1885|work=Weekly Mail|url-status=live|page=3}}</ref> Also from Merthyr Tydfil, he was previously a journalist and contributor to the magazine. He continued as editor until June 1887 when the last number was published. The magazine was printed in Cardiff by ''Daniel Owen & Company.''<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3234530/3234534/67/|title=Death of Mr James Harris of Cardiff|date=5 December 1892|work=Evening Express|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref>\n\nAs well as writing extensively for the magazine themselves, the editors assembled a group of regular contributors \"who had had an English scholastic training.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Though traditional and conservative in outlook, the magazine featured a number of women authors, including [[Amy Dillwyn]], Kate Dodd, Jeanette Forsyth, and Ella Egerton; and conveyed a \"sense of admiration and affection for working people in Wales\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|22}} ''The Red Dragon'' displayed a \"sustained awareness of the pressures on the poor and a clear-sighted appreciation of the realities of working life\",<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|19}} and treated the lives of working people in Wales \"respectfully and with real interest\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|22}}\n\nSocial and political comment was presented alongside other solid literary content including biographies, poetry and serialised novels. The magazine sought to provide a Welsh perspective on current issues of society, economics and politics, including land ownership and public education, and reported the activities of Welsh members of Parliament. Issues of social difference and the contrast between rural and urban were recurring themes.<ref name=\":0\" /> Regular sections included \"Marginal Notes on Library Books\", \"Literary and Art Notes\", and \"Notes and Queries\"<ref name=\":0\" /> on items of literary and antiquarian interest \"confined to matters relating to Wales and the Border Counties\".<ref>{{Cite journal|date=July 1884|editor-last=Wilkins|editor-first=Charles|title=Notes and Queries|url=https://archive.org/details/reddragon01wilkgoog/page/n119/mode/2up|journal=The Red Dragon|volume=VI|page=92}}</ref>  \n\nThe magazine received numerous favourable reviews in the South Wales newspapers (though Wilkins also wrote for many of the same papers).<ref name=\":13\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4479672/4479675/56/|title='The Red Dragon.'|date=30 January 1882|work=Western Mail|url-status=live|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3513906/3513910/87/|title=The Magazines|date=17 March 1882|work=South Wales Daily News|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3372143/3372146/56/|title='The Red Dragon.'|date=15 April 1882|work=Weekly Mail|url-status=live|page=3}}</ref> Malcolm Ballin's modern study of Welsh periodicals notes that \"At its peak [''The Red Dragon''] commanded for the first time the attention of a newly recognised audience for a Welsh periodical in English.\"<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|22}} The magazine was priced at one shilling (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=0.05|start_year=1882|r=0|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) per issue, though this was halved for the January 1884 to June 1885 issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.library.wales/view/2062893/2062894/|title=The Red Dragon The National Magazine of Wales|website=The National Library of Wales|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe closure of ''The Red Dragon'', in June 1887, was noted with regret in letters to the editors of the local newspapers.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4485054/4485056/14/|title='The Red Dragon.'|date=17 June 1887|work=Western Mail|url-status=live|page=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3373635/3373639/60/|title=Notes and Queries Column for the 'Weekly Mail'|date=18 June 1887|work=Weekly Mail|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> One newspaper editor opined that \"it would appear to be one thing to place before the English-speaking public of Wales high-class reading matter, and quite another thing to make the said English-speaking public appreciate the effort at its true value.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\n''The Red Dragon'' displayed a \"sustained awareness of the pressures on the poor and a clear-sighted appreciation of the realities of working life\"<ref name=\":6\">{{cite book|last=Ballin|first=Malcolm|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2VeuBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA10|title=Welsh Periodicals in English: 1882\u20132012|publisher=University of Wales Press|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7083-2615-2|location=Cardiff|pages=10\u201322}}</ref>{{Rp|19}} and treated the lives of working people in Wales \"respectfully and with real interest\".<ref name=\":6\" />{{Rp|22}} The magazine continues to be valuable to modern scholars as a historical resource, created in response to the \"urgent need to rescue and record such traditional lore which was then rapidly fading from memory\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=James|first=Brian Ll|date=2003|title=John Howells of St Athan|url=https://journals.library.wales/view/1169834/1175421/126|journal=Morgannwg|volume=XLVII|pages=119\u2013121}}</ref>{{Rp|119}}\n\n== Issues ==\n* 1882: Vol. I. Nos.1\u20136: [[iarchive:reddragon00unkngoog/page/n7/mode/2up|February to July]]; Vol. II. Nos. 7\u201311: [[iarchive:reddragon03wilkgoog/page/n15/mode/2up|August to December]]\n* 1883: Vol. III. Nos.1\u20136: [[iarchive:reddragonnation00wilkgoog/page/n8/mode/2up|January to June]]; Vol. IV. Nos. 7\u201312: [[iarchive:reddragonnation01unkngoog/page/n10/mode/2up|July to December]]\n* 1884: Vol. V. Nos.1\u20136: [[iarchive:reddragon00wilkgoog/page/n7/mode/2up|January to June]]; Vol. VI. Nos. 7\u201312: [[iarchive:reddragon01wilkgoog/page/n11/mode/2up|July to December]]\n* 1885: Vol. VII. Nos.1\u20136: [https://journals.library.wales/view/2062893/2066717/ January to June]; Vol. VIII. Nos. 7\u201312: [https://journals.library.wales/view/2062893/2067408/ July to December]\n* 1886: Vol. IX. Nos.1\u20136: [https://journals.library.wales/view/2062893/2068163/ January to June]; Vol. X. Nos. 7\u201312: [https://journals.library.wales/view/2062893/2068872/ July to December]\n*1887: Vol. XI. Nos.1\u20136: [[iarchive:reddragonnation00unkngoog/page/n7/mode/2up|January to June]] (including an ''Index to our Notes and Queries from the Commencement to December 1886'')\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://journals.library.wales/view/2062893/2062894/ \"The Red Dragon The National Magazine of Wales\"]. ''The National Library of Wales. Welsh Journals''. Retrieved 28 February 2020. (Alternative source for magazine issues February 1882 \u2013 April 1887.)\n*[https://books.google.com.au/books?id=3hYJAQAAIAAJ&q=%22To+my+readers%2C+subscribers%22 The Red Dragon: The National Magazine of Wales, Volume XI: January to June 1887]. (This link provides limited access to Harris' valedictory letter in the June 1887 issue on the closure of the magazine which is not available in the online sources given above.)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Dragon, The}}\n[[Category:Periodicals published in Wales]]\n[[Category:Welsh magazines]]\n[[Category:British monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:British history magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1882]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1887]]\n[[Category:Defunct British literary magazines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Welsh literary periodical (1882\u20131887)}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = The Red Dragon\n| logo            = \n| logo_size       = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_file      = The_Red_Dragon_periodical_cover_page_February_1882.jpg<!-- cover.jpg (omit the \"file:\" prefix) -->\n| image_size      = <!-- default is 180px -->\n| image_alt       =printed title page showing the magazine name in embellished script around a sketch of a dragon \n| image_caption   = Motto: {{Lang|cy|Y Ddraig Goch A Ddyry Gychwyn.}}<br/>\"The Red Dragon Will Lead The Way.\"\n| editor          = [[Charles Wilkins (writer)|Charles Wilkins]] 1882\u20131885\n| editor2         = James Harris 1885\u20131887<!-- up to |editor5= -->\n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| photographer    = \n| category        = Welsh history and literature\n| frequency       = Monthly\n| format          = \n| publisher       = Daniel Owen & Co. ([[Cardiff]], [[Wales]])\n| paid_circulation   = \n| unpaid_circulation = \n| total_circulation  = \n| founder         = Charles Wilkins\n| founded         = \n| firstdate       = February 1882<!-- {{Start date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| finaldate       = June 1887<!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| country         = Wales\n| language        = English\n| website         = [https://journals.library.wales/view/2062893/2062894/ The National Library of Wales: Welsh Journals]<!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''''The Red Dragon''''', '''''The National Magazine of Wales''''', was a monthly [[English language|English-language]] literary [[magazine]] published in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]], from February 1882 until June 1887 and edited by [[Charles Wilkins (writer)|Charles Wilkins]] until July 1885 when James Harris took over.\n\nAlthough directed primarily at the people of [[South Wales]], it was intended \"to make known to the greater English world the characteristics and aims of the Welsh people and the beauties of their language and literature\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4485019/4485021/14/|title=The End of Another National Venture|date=9 June 1887|work=Western Mail|url-status=live|page=2}}</ref> The magazine included articles on the [[history of Wales]] (emphasising its recent history), [[Biography|biographies]], [[poetry]] and [[serial novel]]s.\n\nThe closure of the magazine elicited numerous expressions of regret in local newspapers in 1887. ''The Red Dragon'' remains a useful historical resource for modern scholars as a record of traditional lore.\n\n== Background ==\nThe 1880s was a pivotal time of social change for Wales, especially in terms of the effects of [[industrialisation]] on traditional rural culture, language, religion, education, and politics. Three-quarters of the population spoke [[Welsh language|Welsh]] (though most not exclusively) but a [[Middle class|middle-class]] culture had developed that identified English with business and success.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last=Ballin|first=Malcolm|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2VeuBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA10|title=Welsh Periodicals in English: 1882\u20132012|publisher=University of Wales Press|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7083-2615-2|location=Cardiff|pages=10\u201322}}</ref> While there were \"articulate and powerful groups of business and professional Welshmen who congregated in London\",<ref>{{Cite book|last=Morgan|first=Kenneth O.|title=Rebirth of a Nation: A History of Modern Wales|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1981|isbn=|location=Oxford|page=6, cited in Ballin (2013), p. 11.|pages=}}</ref> Wales was considered by many British people to be little more than a pic