raft|1993]] || 1 || 1 || 1 || [[Chris Webber]] || [[Orlando Magic]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| 1993 || 2 || 6 || 33 || [[Eric Riley]] || [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| [[1994 NBA Draft|1994]] || 1 || 5 || 5 || [[Juwan Howard]] || [[Washington Bullets]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| 1994 || 1 || 13 || 13 || [[Jalen Rose]] || [[Denver Nuggets]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| [[1995 NBA Draft|1995]] || 2 || 6 || 35 || [[Jimmy King]] || [[Toronto Raptors]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]]\n*[[List of vacated and forfeited games in college basketball]]\n*[[University of Michigan basketball scandal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Michigan Wolverines men's basketball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1992-93 Michigan Wolverines Men's Basketball Team}}\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines men's basketball seasons]]\n[[Category:1992\u201393 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|Michigan]]\n[[Category:NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament Final Four seasons]]\n[[Category:1993 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament participants|Michigan]]\n[[Category:1992 in sports in Michigan|Michigan]]\n[[Category:1993 in sports in Michigan|Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |mode=Basketball\n  |year=1992\u201393\n  |prev_year=1991\u201392\n  |next_year=1993\u201394\n  |team=Michigan Wolverines\n  |image=\n  |image_size=150\n  | logo = Michigan Wolverines Logo.svg\n  | logo_size = 200\n  | logo_alt = A blue block M with maize-colored borders and the word Michigan across the middle.\n  |conference=Big Ten Conference\n  |division=\n  |short_conf=Big Ten\n  |CoachRank= 2\n  |APRank= 3\n  |record= 0-4 (31-5 [[University of Michigan basketball scandal#Vacated and forfeited games|unadjusted]])\n  |conf_record= 0-3\n  |head_coach=[[Steve Fisher]]\n  |asst_coach1=[[Brian Dutcher]]\n  |asst_coach2=[[Jay Smith (basketball)|Jay Smith]]\n  |asst_coach3=[[Perry Watson]]\n  |captain=Rotating\n  |mvp=[[Chris Webber]]\n  |stadium=[[Crisler Arena]]\n  |champion=\n  |bowl=[[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]\n  |bowl_result=[[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship Game|Runner Up]] (vacated)\n}}\n{{1992\u201393 Big Ten Conference men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''1992\u201393 [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball]] team''' represented the [[University of Michigan]] in intercollegiate [[college basketball]] during the [[1992\u201393 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1992\u201393 season]]. The team played its home games in the [[Crisler Arena]] in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], and was a member of the [[Big Ten Conference]].  Under the direction of [[head coach]] [[Steve Fisher]], the team finished second in the Big Ten Conference.<ref name=BTMG68>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|title=Big Ten Basketball 2009-10 Media Guide|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|page=69|accessdate=2010-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703173409/http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|archive-date=2010-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Although the team compiled a 31-5 record during the season, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] has [[University of Michigan basketball scandal#Vacated and forfeited games|adjusted]] the team's record to 0-4 due to the [[University of Michigan basketball scandal]].<ref name=DIR56>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/m_basketball_RB/2010/D1.pdf|title=Division I Records|accessdate=2010-09-23|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|page=56}}</ref>  The team earned an invitation to the [[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] where it was national runner up.<ref name=UMNCAA3>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-ncaa-tournament|title=NCAA Tournament History|publisher=University of Michigan|page=3|year=2010|accessdate=2010-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001104827/http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-ncaa-tournament|archive-date=2010-10-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> The team was ranked for the entire eighteen weeks of [[AP Poll|Associated Press Top Twenty-Five Poll]], starting the season ranked first, holding the number one position for three weeks and ending ranked third,<ref name=DIR6883>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/m_basketball_RB/2010/D1.pdf|title=Division I Records|accessdate=2010-08-28|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|pages=68&ndash;83}}</ref> and it ended the season ranked fourth in the final [[Coaches' Poll|USA Today/CNN Poll]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/m_basketball_RB/2010/D1.pdf|title=Division I Records|accessdate=2010-08-28|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|page=87}}</ref>  The team had an 8&ndash;5 record against ranked opponents, including the following victories: December 28, 1992, against #20 [[1992\u201393 Nebraska Cornhuskers men's basketball team|Nebraska]] 88&ndash;73 in the [[Rainbow Classic]] at the [[Blaisdell Center]], December 29 against #5 [[1992\u201393 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina]] 79&ndash;78 in the Rainbow Classic, December 30 against #2 [[1992\u201393 Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball team|Kansas]] 86&ndash;74 in the Rainbow Classic, January 7, 1993, against #9 {{cbb link|1992|sex=men|team=Purdue Boilermakers|school=Purdue University|title=Purdue}} 80&ndash;70 at [[Mackey Arena]], February 2 against #25 [[1992\u201393 Michigan State Spartans men's basketball team|Michigan State]] 73&ndash;69 at the [[Breslin Student Events Center]], February 7 against #19 Purdue 84&ndash;76 at [[Crisler Arena]], March 2 against #15 [[1992\u201393 Iowa Hawkeyes men's basketball team|Iowa]] 82&ndash;73 at Crisler Arena, April 2 against #2 Kentucky 81&ndash;78 (OT) at the [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome|Superdome]] in the [[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]].<ref name=TTY45>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-through-the-years|title=Through The Years|accessdate=2010-09-20|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|page=45|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100902071019/http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-through-the-years|archive-date=2010-09-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe team had rotating [[captain (sports)|captain]]s on a game-by-game basis, and [[Chris Webber]] earned team [[MVP]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-all-time-accolades|title=All-Time Accolades|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|pages=9&ndash;10|accessdate=2010-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901151320/http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-all-time-accolades|archive-date=2010-09-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The team's leading scorers were Chris Webber (690 points), [[Jalen Rose]] (555 points), and [[Juwan Howard]] (524 points).  The leading rebounders were Webber (362), Howard (267), and [[Eric Riley]] (169).<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's Basketball Statistic Archive Query Page |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |website=MGoBlue.com |url=http://stats.ath.umich.edu/basketball/basketstart.php |accessdate=September 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418044313/http://stats.ath.umich.edu/basketball/basketstart.php |archivedate=April 18, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the season the team set a Big Ten Conference record for single-season [[blocked shot]]s (193) that would last until 2000.<ref name=BTMG29>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|title=Big Ten Basketball 2009-10 Media Guide|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|page=29|accessdate=2010-09-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703173409/http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|archive-date=2010-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDuring the season, the team won the Big Ten Conference statistical championships in [[rebound (basketball)|rebounding]] and rebounding margin with at 40.9 average and 7.6 average margin in conference games, respectively.<ref name=BTMG38>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|title=Big Ten Basketball 2009-10 Media Guide|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|page=38|accessdate=2010-09-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703173409/http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|archive-date=2010-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The record-setting team also led the conference in average blocked shots (5.0).<ref name=BTMG38/> [[Chris Webber]] led the Big Ten in rebounds with a 9.7 average in 18 conference games and 10.1 average in 36 overall games.<ref name=BTMG34>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|title=Big Ten Basketball 2009-10 Media Guide|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|page=34|accessdate=2010-09-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703173409/http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|archive-date=2010-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=BTMG35>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|title=Big Ten Basketball 2009-10 Media Guide|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|page=35|accessdate=2010-09-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703173409/http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/BT|archive-date=2010-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe team surpassed the 30-win total by the 1989 team with 31 victories and was the winningest team in school history, until being matched by Michigan's [[2012\u201313 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2012\u201313 team]] and later being surpassed by its [[2017\u201318 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2017\u201318 team]].<ref name=DIR16>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/m_basketball_RB/2010/D1.pdf|title=Division I Records|accessdate=2010-09-18|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|page=16}}</ref>\n\nFor the second year in a row, the team set the school record for single-season team blocks with 193 in 36 games, surpassing the 182 in 34 games set the prior year.  The record would stand until 2007.<ref name=ATR19>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-all-time-records|title=All-Time Records|accessdate=2010-09-18|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|page=19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401053824/http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-all-time-records|archive-date=2011-04-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFour players surpassed Jalen Rose's single-season minutes played record set the prior season.  Rose set the new and current single-season record of 1234.  King played 1174 minutes, while Webber and Howard contributed 1138 and 1135, respectively.<ref name=ATR20>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-all-time-records|title=All-Time Records|accessdate=2010-09-09|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|page=20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401053824/http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-all-time-records|archive-date=2011-04-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Regular season==\nMichigan returned its top nine scorers and began the season ranked number one in the country by the [[Associated Press]].<ref>{{cite news|title=U-M At Top Of The Polls|date=1992-11-17|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Stoda, Greg}}</ref>  Michigan lost its second game of the season in a rematch with [[1992\u201393 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Top Tow Take a Tumble \u2013 Duke, Kansas knock Off Michigan (1), Indiana (2) |date=1992-12-06|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Adande, J. A.|page=1, sports section}}</ref>\n\n<!--Mar 11 @ ILL - Illinois student section the Orange Crush chanted \"Crack House\" at Jalen Rose during the game-->\n\n==Schedule==\n\n{{CBB schedule start\n| rank      = yes\n| gamehighs = yes\n| attend    = yes\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 1, 1992\n| nonconf      = yes\n| time         = \n| tv           = \n| seed         = \n| rank         = 1\n| away         = yes\n| neutral      = \n| oppseed      = \n| opprank      = \n| opponent     = Rice\n| gamename     = \n| w/l          = w\n| score        = 75\u201371\n| overtime     = \n| record       = 1\u20130\n| conference   = \n| highscorer   = {{nbsp}}\n| points       = \n| highrebounder= {{nbsp}}\n| rebounds     = \n| highassister = {{nbsp}}\n| assists      = \n| site_stadium = {{nbsp}}\n| attend       = \n| site_cityst  = [[Houston, TX]]\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 5, 1992\n| nonconf      = yes\n| time         = \n| tv           = \n| seed         = \n| rank         = 1\n| away         = yes\n| neutral      = \n| oppseed      = \n| opprank      = 4\n| opponent     = Duke\n| gamename     = \n| w/l          = l\n| score        = 68\u201379\n| overtime     = \n| record       = 1\u20131\n| conference   = \n| highscorer   = {{nbsp}}\n| points       = \n| highrebounder= {{nbsp}}\n| rebounds     = \n| highassister = {{nbsp}}\n| assists      = \n| site_stadium = [[Cameron Indoor Stadium]]\n| attend       = \n| site_cityst  = [[Durham, NC]]\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = December 7, 1992\