bounder= {{nbsp}}\n| rebounds     = \n| highassister = {{nbsp}}\n| assists      = \n| site_stadium = Kingdome\n| attend       = \n| site_cityst  = Seattle, WA\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = April 3, 1993\n| nonconf      = yes\n| time         = \n| tv           = \n| seed         = \n| rank         = 3\n| away         = \n| neutral      = yes\n| oppseed      = \n| opprank      = 2\n| opponent     = Kentucky\n| gamename     = NCAA Tournament \u2022 National Semifinals\n| w/l          = w\n| score        = 81\u201378\n| overtime     = OT\n| record       = 31\u20134\n| conference   = \n| highscorer   = {{nbsp}}\n| points       = \n| highrebounder= {{nbsp}}\n| rebounds     = \n| highassister = {{nbsp}}\n| assists      = \n| site_stadium = [[Superdome]]\n| attend       = \n| site_cityst  = [[New Orleans, LA]]\n}}\n{{CBB schedule entry\n| date         = April 5, 1993\n| nonconf      = yes\n| time         = \n| tv           = CBS\n| seed         = \n| rank         = 3\n| away         = \n| neutral      = yes\n| oppseed      = \n| opprank      = 4\n| opponent     = North Carolina\n| gamename     = NCAA Tournament \u2022 National Final\n| w/l          = l\n| score        = 71\u201377\n| overtime     = \n| record       = 31\u20135\n| conference   = \n| highscorer   = Webber\n| points       = 23\n| highrebounder= Webber\n| rebounds     = 11\n| highassister = ''Tied''\n| assists      = 4\n| site_stadium = Superdome\n| attend       = \n| site_cityst  = New Orleans, LA\n}}\n{{CBB schedule end\n| rank     = \n| poll     = \n| timezone = \n| region  = W\n| regionname = West \n| notes = \n}}\n\n==NCAA tournament==\nMichigan was given the #1 seed in that year's West Regional and played their first and second-round games at the [[McKale Center]] in [[Tucson]]. They defeated {{cbb link|1992|sex=men|team=Coastal Carolina Chanticleers|school=Coastal Carolina University|title=Coastal Carolina}} in their first game and then were taken to overtime by #9 seed [[1992\u201393 UCLA Bruins men's basketball team|UCLA]] before escaping with a victory.\n\nThe Wolverines moved on to the [[Kingdome]] for the regionals. The sub-regional had been littered with upsets, as the #12, #13, and #15 seeds had all won in the first round. Michigan drew #12 seeded {{cbb link|1992|sex=men|team=George Washington Colonials|school=George Washington University|title=George Washington}} and won, then faced {{cbb link|1992|sex=men|team=Temple Owls|school=Temple University|title=Temple}} for the second consecutive year (having defeated them as a #6 seed the year before) and beating them 77&ndash;72 to join [[1992-93 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]], [[1992-93 Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball team|Kansas]], and [[1992-93 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina]] in the Final Four in [[New Orleans]].\nIn their national semifinal at the [[Louisiana Superdome|Superdome]] on April 3, the team defeated Southeast Regional winner [[1992\u201393 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]] 81&ndash;78 in overtime.\n\nIn the [[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship Game|championship game]] at the Superdome on April 5, the Wolverines lost to East Regional winner [[1992\u201393 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina]] 77&ndash;71. Michigan's final possession of the game went down as one of the most memorable moments in college basketball history. With twenty seconds to go and Michigan trailing by two and out of timeouts, Chris Webber rebounded a missed free throw. Confused as to what to do next, Webber thought about passing to Jalen Rose but did not and took a step without dribbling the basketball. The officials did not see the travel, however, and Webber headed upcourt where North Carolina was set up in a half court trap defense. Webber ran directly into the trap and was double teamed in the corner. He could not break the double team to pass the ball, and called for a timeout that the Wolverines did not have. By rule, Michigan was given a technical foul for calling the extra timeout and North Carolina was given two free throws and possession of the ball. North Carolina made their free throws, then added two more when Michigan was forced to foul again after the change in possession.<ref name=UMNCAA3/><ref name=TTY45/>\n\nThe team established numerous NCAA records for [[three-point field goal]]s in the [[final four]]: fewest single-game three-point field goals made in a final four (0 vs. [[1992\u201393 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]] on April 3, 1993, in an [[overtime (sports)|overtime]]) and fewest single-game three-point field goals attempted (4 vs. Kentucky).<ref name=TFF10>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/m_final4/2010/2010Final4.pdf|title=The Final Four|accessdate=2010-09-16|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|page=10}}</ref>  The 0 three-point field goals made surpassed the team's previous record of 1 made against [[1991\u201392 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]] the year before in the [[1992 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]].<ref name=TFF10/>\n\n==Later developments==\nIn 2002, the Wolverines vacated their entire 1992\u201393 season, including their tournament appearance, in the wake of a [[University of Michigan basketball scandal|major scandal]] involving many years of improper payments from a major booster to several former players, among them Webber.\n\n==Statistics==\nThe team posted the following statistics:<ref name=MBSAQ>{{cite web|url=http://stats.ath.umich.edu/basketball/basketstart.php |title=Men's Basketball Statistic Archive Query Page |accessdate=2010-03-28 |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418044313/http://stats.ath.umich.edu/basketball/basketstart.php |archivedate=18 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''Name'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''GP'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''GS'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''Min'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''Avg'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Field goal (basketball)|FG]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''FGA'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''FG%'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Three point shot|3FG]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''3FGA'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''3FG%'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Free throw|FT]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''FTA'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''FT%'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''OR'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''DR'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Rebound (basketball)|RB]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''Avg'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Assist (basketball)|Ast]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''Avg'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Foul (basketball)|PF]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''DQ'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''TO'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Steal (basketball)|Stl]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Blocked shot|Blk]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''[[Point (basketball)|Pts]]'''\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''Avg'''\n|-\n| [[Chris Webber]]* ||36||36||1138||31.6||281||454||0.619||27||80||0.338||101||183||0.552||155||207||362||10.1||90||2.5||102||4||105||49||90||690||19.2\n|-\n| [[Jalen Rose]] ||36||36||1234||34.3||203||455||0.446||33||103||0.320||116||161||