\n| poll5_13=\n| poll5_14=\n| poll5_15=\n| poll5_16=\n| poll5_17=\n| poll5_18=\n| poll5_19=\n| poll5_20=\n}}\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* Chris Webber, All-America selection (vacated as a result of the scandal)\n* [[Rob Pelinka]], [[Walter Byers Scholarship|Walter Byers Scholar]] (top male scholar-athlete in all NCAA sports; not vacated)\n\n==Team players drafted into the NBA==\nFive players from this team were selected in the [[NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/draft/NBA_1993.html|title=1993 NBA Draft|publisher=Basketball-reference.com|accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/draft/NBA_1994.html|title=1994 NBA Draft|publisher=Basketball-reference.com|accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/draft/NBA_1995.html|title=1995 NBA Draft|publisher=Basketball-reference.com|accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"80%\"\n|- align=\"center\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Michigan Wolverines|color=white}}\"\n| '''Year''' || '''Round''' || '''Pick''' || '''Overall''' || '''Player''' || '''NBA Club'''\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| [[1993 NBA Draft|1993]] || 1 || 1 || 1 || [[Chris Webber]] || [[Orlando Magic]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| 1993 || 2 || 6 || 33 || [[Eric Riley]] || [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| [[1994 NBA Draft|1994]] || 1 || 5 || 5 || [[Juwan Howard]] || [[Washington Bullets]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| 1994 || 1 || 13 || 13 || [[Jalen Rose]] || [[Denver Nuggets]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n| [[1995 NBA Draft|1995]] || 2 || 6 || 35 || [[Jimmy King]] || [[Toronto Raptors]]\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1993 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]]\n*[[List of vacated and forfeited games in college basketball]]\n*[[University of Michigan basketball scandal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Michigan Wolverines men's basketball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1992-93 Michigan Wolverines Men's Basketball Team}}\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines men's basketball seasons]]\n[[Category:1992\u201393 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|Michigan]]\n[[Category:NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament Final Four seasons]]\n[[Category:1993 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament participants|Michigan]]\n[[Category:1992 in sports in Michigan|Michigan]]\n[[Category:1993 in sports in Michigan|Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSuperdome(link changed toMercedes-Benz Superdome) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1992%E2%80%9393_Michigan_Wolverines_men%27s_basketball_team"}
{"title_page": "Hughie Ferguson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Hughie Ferguson\n| image = \n| fullname = Hugh Ferguson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1895|3|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1930|1|8|1895|3|4|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Dundee]], Scotland\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Centre forward|Centre forward]]\n| youthyears1 = 1914\u20131916 |youthclubs1 = [[Parkhead Juniors]]\n| years1 = 1916\u20131925 |clubs1 = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]     |caps1 = 288   |goals1 = 284\n| years2 = 1925\u20131929 |clubs2 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] |caps2 = 117 |goals2 = 77\n| years3 = 1929\u20131930 |clubs3 = [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]             |caps3 = 17  |goals3 = 2\n| totalcaps = 422   | totalgoals = 363              \n| nationalyears1 = 1920\u20131922\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 =3\n }}\n'''Hugh Ferguson''' (2 March 1895 \u2013 8 January 1930) was a Scottish [[Association football|footballer]]. One of only seven men in the history of the English and Scottish Football Leagues to have scored 350 League goals, he began his career at [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] and established himself as a consistent scorer, finishing as the top goalscorer in the [[Scottish Football League]] on three occasions between 1918 and 1921. His 284 league goals remains a record at the club.\n\nIn 1925, he moved to [[Football League First Division]] side [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] and continued his scoring exploits, including scoring the winning goals in the [[1927 FA Cup Final]], in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], and the [[1927 FA Charity Shield]], in a 2\u20131 victory over amateur side [[Corinthians F.C.|Corinthians]], making Cardiff the only non-English team to have ever won the [[FA Cup]] or the [[FA Charity Shield]]. Despite his prolific scoring record,<ref name=\"Cup friends reunited\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7328650.stm |title=Cup friends reunited |publisher=BBC |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 January 2010 |accessdate=28 August 2010}}</ref> finishing his career with a goal average of 0.855 per game,<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\">{{Cite news |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/sport/Tragic-Scots-FA-Cup-hero.3857688.jp |title=Tragic Scots FA Cup hero who took his own life |publisher=Johnston Press|work=The Scotsman |date=8 March 2008 |accessdate=28 August 2010}}</ref> he was never capped for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]. He finished his career with a short spell with [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] which ended when he committed suicide on 8 January 1930 at the age of 34.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Early career===\nRenowned for his modesty and sense of fair play,<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/> Ferguson started his career with [[Parkhead Juniors]] in 1914. He appeared for the side in their victorious 1914\u201315 [[Scottish Junior Cup]] final.\n\n===Motherwell===\nFerguson joined [[John Hunter (footballer, born 1878)|John Hunter]]'s [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] for the start of the 1916\u201317 season, scoring both goals in the 2\u20132 draw with [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] on 19 August 1916. He soon established himself as a prolific goalscorer at [[Fir Park]], becoming the top [[Scottish Football League]] goalscorer on three occasions (1917\u201318; 1919\u201320; 1920\u201321), scoring 111 goals in total. His 43 goals in 1921 is the second highest season total of League goals in England or Scotland before the change to the [[Offside (association football)|offside law]] in 1925. His scoring exploits attracted interest from several English clubs and, in June 1922, [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] submitted an offer of \u00a33,500 which was rejected by Motherwell who valued Ferguson at \u00a34,000. City would later return with an improved bid of \u00a33,900 which was accepted by the Motherwell board but the transfer collapsed when Ferguson turned down the move.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.motherwellfc.co.uk/the-club/history/club-history/1918-1929/ |title=1918-1929 |publisher=Motherwell F.C. |accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n \nWith Motherwell, Ferguson reached the [[Scottish Cup]] quarter-finals in 1921 and 1922, the semi-finals in 1923, losing 2\u20130 to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], and achieved third place in the League in 1920.<ref>[http://members.lycos.co.uk/kissmyzeus/pa/ferguson.html WELLnet -> pa -> hughie ferguson<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDespite his performance, the dominance of [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] player [[Andy Cunningham (footballer)|Andy Cunningham]] and, later, [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]'s high scoring [[Andrew Nesbit Wilson|Andy Wilson]] meant they were picked for Scotland ahead of Ferguson. He represented the [[Scottish League XI]] three times, scoring three goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/hughferguson.html|title=Hugh Ferguson|work=Londonhearts.com|publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club|accessdate=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Cardiff City===\nIn 1925, halfway through the season and after scoring his 285th goal for Motherwell, Ferguson departed for South Wales, joining FA Cup Finalists [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] for a fee of \u00a35,000, just \u00a31,000 less than the record transfer fee at the time.<ref name=\"Cup friends reunited\"/> Such was his popularity at the Scottish club that the local steelworks closed for over an hour as the workers lined the streets to wave Ferguson off.<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/> In the previous few seasons, Cardiff had trawled far and wide for talented players and Ferguson was one of a list of notable Scots to wear the blue shirt; Scottish internationals [[Jimmy Blair (footballer born 1918)|Jimmy Blair]] and [[James Nelson (Scottish footballer)|Jimmy Nelson]] had both appeared for the club. He a goalscoring debut for the club on 7 November 1925 in a 5\u20132 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Who's Who of Cardiff City | first = Dean | last = Hayes | publisher = Breedon Books | year = 2006 | page=63 | location=Derby | isbn= 1-85983-462-0}}</ref>\n\nFerguson's most successful moment in English football occurred when he appeared for Cardiff in the 1927 Cup Final against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Having scored five times on the way to the final, in the 74th minute, collecting a throw from the right, Ferguson hurried a tame shot toward the Arsenal goal. [[Dan Lewis (footballer)|Dan Lewis]], the Arsenal goalkeeper, appeared to collect the ball but, under pressure from the advancing [[Len Davies]], clumsily allowed the ball to roll through his grasp; in a desperate attempt to retrieve the ball, Lewis only succeeded in knocking the ball with his elbow into his own net.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/walesonair/database/facup.shtml BBC Wales On Air - The 1927 FA Cup] contains slow-motion replay footage of the goal</ref> [[Ernie Curtis]], the 19\u2011year\u2011old centre-wing said of the goal:\n\n:\"''I was in line with the edge of the [[penalty area]] on the right when Hughie Ferguson hit the shot which Arsenal's goalie ( had crouched down for a little early. The ball spun as it travelled towards him, having taken a slight deflection so he was now slightly out of line with it. Len Davies was following the shot in and I think Dan must have had one eye on him. The result was that he didn't take it cleanly and it squirmed under him and over the line. Len jumped over him and into the net, but never actually touched it.''\"<ref>Derrick Jenkins and Ceri Stennett, ''Wembley 1927''</ref>\n\nFerguson still features on the record books for Cardiff City, having scored five goals in the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] fixture with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 1 September 1928 and his 32 goals in all competitions in the 1926\u201327 season stood until [[Robert Earnshaw]] overtook it in March 2003.<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/> He also scored the first goal in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Corinthian F.C.|the Corinthians]] in the 1927\u201328 [[1927 FA Charity Shield|Charity Shield]] and his two goals won the [[Welsh Cup]] later that same season for Cardiff against [[Bangor F.C.|Bangor]]; but despite a healthy return of 77 goals during his four seasons there his days at [[Ninian Park]] were numbered due to a back injury.\n\n===Dundee===\nFerguson returned to Scotland with [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] in the following season for a fee of \u00a3500, but his days there were desperate; a despondent, demanding crowd seeking from the legendary goalscorer more than he could provide. He scored two goals for Dundee, before being dropped due to injury and a lack of form. His final game for the club was a 3\u20130 victory over [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] on 14 December 1929.<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/>\n\n==Death==\nFerguson sank into depression and on 8 January 1930 committed [[suicide]], [[Poison gas|gassing]] himself at [[Dens Park]] after a training session. He was aged 34, and left behind his wife Jessie and two children.<ref name=\"Cup friends reunited\"/> Ferguson's family have attributed his death to ''an imbalance of his inner-ear'' which they believe was caused by an undiagnosed brain tumour.<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/>\n\n==Family==\nFerguson's son Jack later went on to represent Britain in [[water polo]] at the [[1952 Summer Olympics|1952]] and [[1956 Summer Olympics|1956]] Olympics.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/ferguson-reflects-on-past-as-he-enters-university-s-hall-of-fame-1.856980 |title=Ferguson reflects on past as he enters university's Hall of Fame |publisher=The Herald |date=28 April 2007 |accessdate=22 June 2015 | first=Doug | last=Gillon}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\nMotherwell\n\n*1916\u201317 - 24 League goals;\n*1917\u201318 - 35\n*1918\u201319 - 19\n*1919\u201320 - 33\n*1920\u201321 - 43\n*1921\u201322 - 32\n*1922\u201323 - 30\n*1923\u201324 - 28\n*1924\u201325 - 28\n*1925\u201326 - 12\n*Total 284\n\nCardiff City\n\n*1925\u201326 - 19\n*1926\u201327 - 26\n*1927\u201328 - 18\n*1928\u201329 - 14\n*Total 77\n\nDundee\n\n*1929\u201330 - 2; 17 appearances\n*Total 2\n\nCareer\n\n* 1916\u201317 - 1929\u201330 363 goals.\n\n==Honours==\n;Cardiff City\n*'''[[FA Cup]] winner: 1'''\n:: [[FA Cup Final 1927|1927]]\n*'''[[FA Community Shield]] winner: 1'''\n:: [[1927 FA Charity Shield|1927]]\n*'''[[Welsh Cup]] winner: 1'''\n:: 1928\n*'''[[Welsh Cup]] runner-up: 1'''\n:: 1929\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.11v11.com/index.php?pageID=286&id=8 Details of the 1927 FA Cup Final]\n* [http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/31510 Photo of Cardiff's Cup-winning side]. Ferguson is on the bottom-right.\n* [http://sport.scotsman.com/sport/Tragic-Scots-FA-Cup-hero.3857688.jp Summary of Ferguson's career from ''the Scotsman'']\n\n{{Scottish First Division top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferguson, Hughie}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:Association football players who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Suicides in Scotland]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Scottish league football top scorers]]\n[[Category:Parkhead F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Hughie Ferguson\n| image = \n| fullname = Hugh Ferguson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1895|3|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1930|1|8|1895|3|4|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Dundee]], Scotland\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Centre forward|Centre forward]]\n| youthyears1 = 1914\u20131916 |youthclubs1 = [[Parkhead Juniors]]\n| years1 = 1916\u20131925 |clubs1 = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]     |caps1 = 288   |goals1 = 284\n| years2 = 1925\u20131929 |clubs2 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] |caps2 = 117 |goals2 = 77\n| years3 = 1929\u20131930 |clubs3 = [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]             |caps3 = 17  |goals3 = 2\n| totalcaps = 422   | totalgoals = 363              \n| nationalyears1 = 1920\u20131922\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 =3\n }}\n'''Hugh Ferguson''' (2 March 1895 \u2013 8 January 1930) was a Scottish [[Association football|footballer]]. One of only seven men in the history of the English and Scottish Football Leagues to have scored 350 League goals, he began his career at [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] and established himself as a consistent scorer, finishing as the top goalscorer in the [[Scottish Football League]] on three occasions between 1918 and 1921. His 284 league goals remains a record at the club.\n\nIn 1925, he moved to [[Football League First Division]] side [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] and continued his scoring exploits, including scoring the winning goals in the [[1927 FA Cup Final]], in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], and the [[1927 FA Charity Shield]], in a 2\u20131 victory over amateur side [[Corinthians F.C.|Corinthians]], making Cardiff the only non-English team to have ever won the [[FA Cup]] or the [[FA Charity Shield]]. Despite his prolific scoring record,<ref name=\"Cup friends reunited\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7328650.stm |title=Cup friends reunited |publisher=BBC |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 January 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-28}}</ref> finishing his career with a goal average of 0.855 per game,<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\">{{Cite news |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/sport/Tragic-Scots-FA-Cup-hero.3857688.jp |title=Tragic Scots FA Cup hero who took his own life |publisher=Johnston Press|work=The Scotsman |date=8 March 2008 |accessdate=2010-08-28}}</ref> he was never capped for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]. He finished his career with a short spell with [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] which ended when he committed suicide on 8 January 1930 at the age of 34.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Early career===\nRenowned for his modesty and sense of fair play,<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/> Ferguson started his career with [[Parkhead Juniors]] in 1914. He appeared for the side in their victorious 1914\u201315 [[Scottish Junior Cup]] final.\n\n===Motherwell===\nFerguson joined [[John Hunter (footballer, born 1878)|John Hunter]]'s [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] for the start of the 1916\u201317 season, scoring both goals in the 2\u20132 draw with [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] on 19 August 1916. He soon established himself as a prolific goalscorer at [[Fir Park]], becoming the top [[Scottish Football League]] goalscorer on three occasions (1917\u201318; 1919\u201320; 1920\u201321), scoring 111 goals in total. His 43 goals in 1921 is the second highest season total of League goals in England or Scotland before the change to the [[Offside (association football)|offside law]] in 1925. His scoring exploits attracted interest from several English clubs and, in June 1922, [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] submitted an offer of \u00a33,500 which was rejected by Motherwell who valued Ferguson at \u00a34,000. City would later return with an improved bid of \u00a33,900 which was accepted by the Motherwell board but the transfer collapsed when Ferguson turned down the move.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.motherwellfc.co.uk/the-club/history/club-history/1918-1929/ |title=1918-1929 |publisher=Motherwell F.C. |accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n \nWith Motherwell, Ferguson reached the [[Scottish Cup]] quarter-finals in 1921 and 1922, the semi-finals in 1923, losing 2\u20130 to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], and achieved third place in the League in 1920.<ref>[http://members.lycos.co.uk/kissmyzeus/pa/ferguson.html WELLnet -> pa -> hughie ferguson<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDespite his performance, the dominance of [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] player [[Andy Cunningham (footballer)|Andy Cunningham]] and, later, [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]'s high scoring [[Andrew Nesbit Wilson|Andy Wilson]] meant they were picked for Scotland ahead of Ferguson. He represented the [[Scottish League XI]] three times, scoring three goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/hughferguson.html|title=Hugh Ferguson|work=Londonhearts.com|publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club|accessdate=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Cardiff City===\nIn 1925, halfway through the season and after scoring his 285th goal for Motherwell, Ferguson departed for South Wales, joining FA Cup Finalists [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] for a fee of \u00a35,000, just \u00a31,000 less than the record transfer fee at the time.<ref name=\"Cup friends reunited\"/> Such was his popularity at the Scottish club that the local steelworks closed for over an hour as the workers lined the streets to wave Ferguson off.<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/> In the previous few seasons, Cardiff had trawled far and wide for talented players and Ferguson was one of a list of notable Scots to wear the blue shirt; Scottish internationals [[Jimmy Blair (footballer born 1918)|Jimmy Blair]] and [[James Nelson (Scottish footballer)|Jimmy Nelson]] had both appeared for the club. He a goalscoring debut for the club on 7 November 1925 in a 5\u20132 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Who's Who of Cardiff City | first = Dean | last = Hayes | publisher = Breedon Books | year = 2006 | page=63 | location=Derby | isbn= 1-85983-462-0}}</ref>\n\nFerguson's most successful moment in English football occurred when he appeared for Cardiff in the 1927 Cup Final against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Having scored five times on the way to the final, in the 74th minute, collecting a throw from the right, Ferguson hurried a tame shot toward the Arsenal goal. [[Dan Lewis (footballer)|Dan Lewis]], the Arsenal goalkeeper, appeared to collect the ball but, under pressure from the advancing [[Len Davies]], clumsily allowed the ball to roll through his grasp; in a desperate attempt to retrieve the ball, Lewis only succeeded in knocking the ball with his elbow into his own net.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/walesonair/database/facup.shtml BBC Wales On Air - The 1927 FA Cup] contains slow-motion replay footage of the goal</ref> [[Ernie Curtis]], the 19\u2011year\u2011old centre-wing said of the goal:\n\n:\"''I was in line with the edge of the [[penalty area]] on the right when Hughie Ferguson hit the shot which Arsenal's goalie ( had crouched down for a little early. The ball spun as it travelled towards him, having taken a slight deflection so he was now slightly out of line with it. Len Davies was following the shot in and I think Dan must have had one eye on him. The result was that he didn't take it cleanly and it squirmed under him and over the line. Len jumped over him and into the net, but never actually touched it.''\"<ref>Derrick Jenkins and Ceri Stennett, ''Wembley 1927''</ref>\n\nFerguson still features on the record books for Cardiff City, having scored five goals in the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] fixture with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 1 September 1928 and his 32 goals in all competitions in the 1926\u201327 season stood until [[Robert Earnshaw]] overtook it in March 2003.<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/> He also scored the first goal in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Corinthian F.C.|the Corinthians]] in the 1927\u201328 [[1927 FA Charity Shield|Charity Shield]] and his two goals won the [[Welsh Cup]] later that same season for Cardiff against [[Bangor F.C.|Bangor]]; but despite a healthy return of 77 goals during his four seasons there his days at [[Ninian Park]] were numbered due to a back injury.\n\n===Dundee===\nFerguson returned to Scotland with [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] in the following season for a fee of \u00a3500, but his days there were desperate; a despondent, demanding crowd seeking from the legendary goalscorer more than he could provide. He scored two goals for Dundee, before being dropped due to injury and a lack of form. His final game for the club was a 3\u20130 victory over [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] on 14 December 1929.<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/>\n\n==Death==\nFerguson sank into depression and on 8 January 1930 committed [[suicide]], [[Poison gas|gassing]] himself at [[Dens Park]] after a training session. He was aged 34, and left behind his wife Jessie and two children.<ref name=\"Cup friends reunited\"/> Ferguson's family have attributed his death to ''an imbalance of his inner-ear'' which they believe was caused by an undiagnosed brain tumour.<ref name=\"Tragic Scots FA Cup hero\"/>\n\n==Family==\nFerguson's son Jack later went on to represent Britain in [[water polo]] at the [[1952 Summer Olympics|1952]] and [[1956 Summer Olympics|1956]] Olympics.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/ferguson-reflects-on-past-as-he-enters-university-s-hall-of-fame-1.856980 |title=Ferguson reflects on past as he enters university's Hall of Fame |publisher=The Herald |date=28 April 2007 |accessdate=2015-06-22 | first=Doug | last=Gillon}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\nMotherwell\n\n*1916\u201317 - 24 League goals;\n*1917\u201318 - 35\n*1918\u201319 - 19\n*1919\u201320 - 33\n*1920\u201321 - 43\n*1921\u201322 - 32\n*1922\u201323 - 30\n*1923\u201324 - 28\n*1924\u201325 - 28\n*1925\u201326 - 12\n*Total 284\n\nCardiff City\n\n*1925\u201326 - 19\n*1926\u201327 - 26\n*1927\u201328 - 18\n*1928\u201329 - 14\n*Total 77\n\nDundee\n\n*1929\u201330 - 2; 17 appearances\n*Total 2\n\nCareer\n\n* 1916\u201317 - 1929\u201330 363 goals.\n\n==Honours==\n;Cardiff City\n*'''[[FA Cup]] winner: 1'''\n:: [[FA Cup Final 1927|1927]]\n*'''[[FA Community Shield]] winner: 1'''\n:: [[1927 FA Charity Shield|1927]]\n*'''[[Welsh Cup]] winner: 1'''\n:: 1928\n*'''[[Welsh Cup]] runner-up: 1'''\n:: 1929\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.11v11.com/index.php?pageID=286&id=8 Details of the 1927 FA Cup Final]\n* [http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/31510 Photo of Cardiff's Cup-winning side]. Ferguson is on the bottom-right.\n* [http://sport.scotsman.com/sport/Tragic-Scots-FA-Cup-hero.3857688.jp Summary of Ferguson's career from ''the Scotsman'']\n\n{{Scottish First Division top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferguson, Hughie}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:Association football players who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Suicides in Scotland]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Scottish league football top scorers]]\n[[Category:Parkhead F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hughie_Ferguson"}
